  a curric:Keyword ;
  schema:name "expressionism"@en ;
  schema:description """a style that emphasises emotion and individual perception, often distorting reality for effect"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:15.827819Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keyword-symbolic
  a curric:Keyword ;
  schema:name "symbolic"@en ;
  schema:description """representing something beyond its literal meaning, often used to convey deeper or abstract concepts"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:15.827823Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-discussions-chats-arent-important
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That discussions are just 'chats' and aren't that important."@en ;
  curric:correction """Think about all of the times you may need to use your verbal skills e.g. an interview or presentation. Being able to articulate yourself well verbally is an important skill to have."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.675548Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-long-am-comparing-key-points
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "As long as I am comparing the key points of two sources that is enough."@en ;
  curric:correction """Using both comparative and correlative conjunctions will ensure there is nuance in your comparisons. They will also help keep your comparisons succinct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.675756Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-black-white-imagery-relates-ideas
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That "black" and "white" imagery always relates to ideas of absence and emptiness."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While "black" and "white" imagery can signal a sense of absence and emptiness, we could also interpret them as showing strength and purity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676430Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-time-write-effective-closing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """I don't have time to write an effective closing, I just need to get my work finished!"""@en ;
  curric:correction """The ending is arguably the most important part of the piece of writing. You need to leave your audience with a clear message that is memorable. You will get quicker at writing effective closings the more you practice using specific strategies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676718Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rewriting-improving-responses-waste-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Rewriting and improving responses is a waste of time"@en ;
  curric:correction """How does the process of revising and rewriting develop vocabulary use? How does rewriting support the writing of future responses?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676732Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poet-make-choices-clear-intention
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A poet will always make choices with a clear intention or meaning."@en ;
  curric:correction """Armitage reveals that poetic choices can be deliberately ambiguous, allowing for multiple interpretations and personal responses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poems-deeply-personal-emotional-written
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Most poems are deeply personal or emotional and are written spontaneously from the heart."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Armitage suggests that writing poetry about traumatic events can be a methodical process. He states that keeping some emotional distance can be helpful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.677300Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-person-feel-nervous
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some pupils believe that they are the only person to feel nervous or scared about public speaking."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Most people feel nervous before speaking, even the most experienced public speakers. It's all about understanding what nerves are and how you can manage them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679382Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-content-alone-enough-effective-speech
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Content alone is enough for an effective speech."@en ;
  curric:correction """Consider the most engaging speakers and how they use tone, gestures and eye contact. Giving a speech is so much more than just the words on a page."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679938Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-memorising-speech-script-makes-confident
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That memorising the speech, or having a script, makes for a more confident delivery."""@en ;
  curric:correction """An effective speech will have an element of spontaneity and naturalism about it. Relying on a script, or repeating a speech word for word, can lead to a robotic delivery and a less convincing speech."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680318Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-response-successful-includes-relevant-quotes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A response is successful if it includes relevant quotes."@en ;
  curric:correction """We should aim high in our language analysis. That means going a step further to use the most meaningful evidence as well as looking for patterns in the text that help us gather a collection of evidence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682078Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hamartia-synonym-excessive-ambition
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Hamartia is a synonym for excessive ambition."@en ;
  curric:correction """Consider if students have read any other tragedies. Ask them to consider Othello's hamartia, for example."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682083Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-jekyll-character-responsible-crimes-hyde
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Jekyll is the only character responsible for the crimes of Hyde."@en ;
  curric:correction """A more nuanced understanding of the text explores the complicity of other characters and the decisions they make."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682087Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-primarily-familial-conflict
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "This poem is primarily about familial conflict."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although the speaker and Kate are family relations, the conflict between them is focused on their shared love interest and so their family connection is inconsequential."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682092Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-items-within-scene
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that the more items within a scene they can describe, the better the description."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask them to consider how they can create atmosphere by limiting their focus to 3-4 focal points in the setting and using figurative language"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682107Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-long-words-related-way-effective
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "As long as the words are related in some way it is an effective semantic field."@en ;
  curric:correction """The best semantic fields vary their word types, including verbs, adjectives and nouns that are related in some way."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682112Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-light-symbolises-hope-optimism-literature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That light always symbolises hope and optimism in literature."@en ;
  curric:correction """While light typically symbolises hope and optimism, for Romeo and Juliet it symbolises loss and separation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682118Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-expert-view-adds-credibility-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That any expert view adds credibility to your argument."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ideally, a quotation from an expert should be recent and the expert should have knowledge that is relevant to the topic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682123Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-while-comparing-poems-look-similarities
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "While comparing poems, you should only look for similarities between them."@en ;
  curric:correction """To create an effective comparison, you want to find nuanced differences within overall similarities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682128Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-aim-include-many-punctuation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students should aim to include as many punctuation types as possible."@en ;
  curric:correction """The best writing uses punctuation sparingly to enhance the overall effect of the writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682157Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-chapter-9-takes-place-events
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Chapter 9 takes place after the events in Chapter 8."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask pupils if they were going to put the chapters in chronological order, how would this chapter be numbered? (Answer: Chapter 6)"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682162Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-jekyll-hyde-stereotypically-gothic-novella
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Jekyll and Hyde' is a stereotypically 'Gothic' novella."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst certain elements of 'Jekyll and Hyde' do follow the conventions of the Gothic, others subvert it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682175Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-my-last-duchess-checking-me
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """'My Last Duchess' and 'Checking Out Me History' are written over 100 years apart, thus won't make for the most effective comparison."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When looking at poems to compare, look closely at similarities between big ideas and you can find nuanced links between poems that are written in different socio-political contexts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682184Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-answer-completed-dont-need
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That once an answer is completed you don't need to return to it."@en ;
  curric:correction """It's useful to think of your first response to a question as your first draft and then go back to it and rewrite and edit where necessary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682188Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-subverting-poetic-form-means-critical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Subverting a poetic form means you are being critical of it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Subverting a poetic form means that you are in some way commenting on either the context of the form or the general theme of the form and using that to enhance the meaning of the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682193Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-take-imagery-face-value
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you should take imagery at face value."@en ;
  curric:correction "Imagery in poetry is often metaphorical and symbolises a deeper meaning."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682205Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-considers-romeo-juliet-love
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That everyone considers 'Romeo and Juliet' to be about love."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some critics consider 'Romeo and Juliet' to be primarily about violence and society instead."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682211Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-elizabethan-england-thought-dreams
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That everyone in Elizabethan England thought dreams were profound and important."@en ;
  curric:correction """Mercutio's 'Queen Mab' speech implies that dreams are inconsequential and merely wish-fulfillment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682216Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-male-characters-fully-embody-societal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The male characters fully embody societal expectations of masculinity."@en ;
  curric:correction """Both Gerald and Eric's remorse reveal internal conflict, showing the struggles and complexities inherent in societal expectations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682221Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-scrooge-keeps-his
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils think that Scrooge keeps his money to himself so that he can spend it on himself."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Scrooge's frugality also extends to his own existence: Scrooge refuses to spend money even on himself, choosing to live a meagre lifestyle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682232Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-viv-irrevocably-rejects-formal-education
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Viv irrevocably rejects the formal education system."@en ;
  curric:correction """Viv questions what she is learning and why, but stays within formal education, perhaps because of her chosen university course which may reflect her experiences and identity in a way that her schooling hasn't."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682237Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-book-describes-life
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that this book describes what life is like for the majority of people who live in Malawi."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Draw attention to the fact that the book is an autobiography and, therefore, is about the writer's own experiences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682241Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-tentative-language-makes-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That using tentative language makes your argument seem less convincing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Using tentative language acknowledges that we are exploring poets' intentions and that there are many valid interpretations of a text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682250Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-write-opening-story-without-knowing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can write the opening of a story without knowing the ending."@en ;
  curric:correction """An effective opening builds up the atmosphere in order to lead the reader to the ending; therefore, you have to know what the ending is in order to create a cohesive atmosphere in the opening."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682294Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shakespeare-misogynist-conversely-shakespeare-feminist
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Shakespeare was a misogynist or, conversely, Shakespeare was a feminist."@en ;
  curric:correction """We don't know about Shakespeare's political or social beliefs. The text is there for us to interpret, not define Shakespeare's views."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682298Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mayhew-describes-everything-prison-negative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Mayhew describes everything in the prison in a negative light."@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus on the descriptions of the prisoners. Why does Mayhew present them in this way? What is he trying to say about prisoners?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682307Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-impressive-able-identify-name-structural
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is impressive to be able to identify and name structural techniques in an essay."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is much better to be able to comment on why certain structural techniques have been used and the effects of them, over just naming them in an essay."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682311Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-merely-documents-battle-many
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poem merely documents a battle where many soldiers die."@en ;
  curric:correction "The poem addresses the issues of military error and blind obedience."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682316Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-extended-metaphor-trees-vines-represent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The extended metaphor of trees and vines represent her absent lover."@en ;
  curric:correction """The extended metaphor of a tree symbolises her absent lover whereas the extended metaphor of the vines symbolises her fantastical thoughts of her lover while he is away from her."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-set-pond-couple-walking
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poem is set by a pond where a couple are walking."@en ;
  curric:correction """The poem is set in the present day (for the speaker) and the speaker is looking back on the memory of walking around a pond with their ex-partner."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sheilas-transformation-end-play-entirely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Sheila’s transformation at the end of the play is entirely optimistic, showing that she has completely embraced responsibility and will lead a future free from societal inequality."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While Sheila's growth is significant, her awareness is limited and she’s still part of the system she criticises. Priestley uses her character to show potential for change, but also highlights the ongoing challenges of inequality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682330Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-dont-realise-need-carefully
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often don't realise that they need to carefully consider what the question is asking them."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Before students can plan anything, they need to consider what the question is actually asking them to do. Rephrasing the question can help."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682350Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thinking-poem-anthology-equally-suitable
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Thinking that every poem in the anthology is equally suitable for every potential question."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While there are common links between the poems, some have more tenuous connections than others."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682354Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-read-something-first-time-able
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When we read something for the first time, we are able to take in all of the important information."""@en ;
  curric:correction """We may need to read something over and over again to fully comprehend it. Using active reading strategies can also help us to fully engage with a new text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682359Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-characters-either-fully-conform-fully
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That characters either fully conform or fully subvert stereotypes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Characters often exist within a grey area - they might conform to some aspects of a stereotype but subvert others - just as real people do."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682363Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-four-ghosts-novella
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils think there are only four ghosts in the novella."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pupils forget about the numerous ghosts that Scrooge sees when he looks out of the window at the end of Stave 1."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682390Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-choosing-vocabulary-ideas-important-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Choosing vocabulary and ideas is the most important part of the writing process."@en ;
  curric:correction """Structural features can really elevate your writing, making it more cohesive and impactful so that your reader doesn't lose interest."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682405Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-consider-sophisticated-writing-involves
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often consider that sophisticated writing always involves using complex and challenging vocabulary."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Draw attention to the way very simple words are used to create complex effects."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682426Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rhythm-rhyme-used-make-text
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Rhythm and rhyme are used to make the text sound poetic."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pupils should always link the poet's use of rhythm and rhyme back to their intentions. How does this help explore some of the messages the poet is trying to convey?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-need-shouldnt-use-rhetorical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You don't need to, or shouldn't, use rhetorical devices in your topic or concluding sentences."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Just because the topic sentences introduce the main idea for the paragraph, that does not mean the topic sentence can't be really creative and engaging. It's crucial that it is engaging to motivate the reader to learn more about the topic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682435Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-semantic-fields-equal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All semantic fields are equal."@en ;
  curric:correction """A semantic field based around an abstract noun (regret) is more sophisticated than one based around something simple (e.g. the rain)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682516Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-plot-point-fits-part
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is only one plot point that fits to each part of Freytag's structure."@en ;
  curric:correction """When discussing climax, ask pupils if any other events in the play could be considered the climax."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682520Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-orwell-presents-good-leaders-bad
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Orwell presents \"good\" leaders and \"bad\" leaders."@en ;
  curric:correction """Think about the impact of Mr. Jones and the pigs on the animals' lives. Is it easy to distinguish which one is better or worse?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682525Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-scrooge-evil
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students might think that Scrooge is evil."@en ;
  curric:correction """Scrooge is not evil - he is immoral. A distinction between the two needs to be clarified."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682532Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-present-lots-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think they should present lots of different ideas in an essay."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst you should present lots of different knowledge, the knowledge should all form part of the same idea or argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682572Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-fred-making-fun
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils think that Fred making fun of Scrooge is mean."@en ;
  curric:correction """Fred is shown to have a great sense of humour and this is what he's expressing when talking about his uncle. It is this sense of humour that enables him to remain optimistic despite financial struggle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682585Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-recognise-use-different-perspectives
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may not recognise the use of different perspectives in the poem to represent distance."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that the dual narrative is a stylistic choice of Garland to show the mother telling the story to her own children as if she is not a part of it. She then slowly reveals the pilot is her own father."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682636Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-find-difficult-harmonise-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may find it difficult to harmonise their perspective choice with appropriate metaphors."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Spend time discussing less effective pairings e.g. a tree would would not perceive people in a city as 'ants' but an airplane might."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lady-macbeths-rejection-guilt-2
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Lady Macbeth's rejection of guilt in 2.2 means 5.1's characterisation is inconsistent."""@en ;
  curric:correction "The language in 2.2 foreshadows what is to come."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682648Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-writing-essays-like-creative-writing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Writing essays is not like creative writing, it doesn't matter how you write things so much."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Not writing clearly and accurately can mean excellent ideas can be lost once written down."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682653Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-feels-though-her-cousin
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The speaker feels as though her cousin Kate has ruined her life completely."@en ;
  curric:correction """While the speaker does feel that Kate has stolen the life she deserved/desired, she also feels that she can have the 'last laugh' since she has given birth to the nobleman's son."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-kumukanda-compared-other-anthology-poems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """'Kumukanda' can only be compared to other anthology poems about cultural identity (e.g. 'Jamaican British' and 'The Émigrée'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although poems centred around cultural identity and inner conflict are most obvious choices to compare, you could compare 'Kumukanda' with another poem that focuses on grief and loss (for example 'I Remember, I Remember')."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dharker-grew-wales
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Dharker grew up in Wales."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Wales features in the title of this poem, Dharker moved to Scotland just before her first birthday. She references Glasgow (where she grew up) in the second stanza of the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-vietnam-war-conflict-fought-us
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Vietnam War was a conflict fought between the US and the country of Vietnam."@en ;
  curric:correction """Following the First Indochina War, Vietnam was split into two regions: communist controlled North Vietnam and South Vietnam, controlled by a non-communist government (supported by the US). The Vietnam War was fought between these two regions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682748Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-our-identities-singular-unchanging-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That our identities are a singular, unchanging thing."@en ;
  curric:correction "Our identifies are made up of many things that can change and evolve over time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682753Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-longer-sentences-sophisticated
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students often believe that longer sentences are more sophisticated."@en ;
  curric:correction """Great writing needs to be concise. Students should be aiming for precision, rather than sophistication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682757Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-scrooges-visit-ghost
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that Scrooge's visit with the Ghost of Christmas Present is limited to Christmas Day."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Scrooge's time with the spirit goes beyond Christmas Day - to the Twelfth Day of Christmas, showing how time is manipulated in the novella."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-scrooge-hates-christmas
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that Scrooge hates Christmas because it marks the anniversary of Marley's death."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Scrooge hates Christmas because he views it as a crime against oneself. He resents that people spend money they don't have at Christmas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682808Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-dickens-message-christmas
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that Dickens' message about Christmas is focused solely on the importance of charity."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Dickens uses the many Christmas scenes in this section of the novella to emphasise the importance of community and human connection."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682823Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-ghost-shows-scrooge
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students believe that the ghost shows Scrooge his future and that this will be Scrooge's fate."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The ghost shows Scrooge the "shadows of things that may be". The word "may" is vital, as he suggests that it is never too late to change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682828Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-parable-story-moral
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that a parable is just a story with a moral/didactic message."@en ;
  curric:correction """The word 'parable' relates specifically to the stories told by Jesus in the Gospels. A story with a moral/didactic message is an allegory."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-placing-ambiguous-short-questions-direct
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Placing ambiguous, short questions with direct address at the end of sentences is an effective rhetorical question. For example: 'Do you/don't you agree?'"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Think about the purpose of a rhetorical question and why we use them. Is this the best way to challenge and provoke thought or get a reaction from your audience?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682837Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sibilance-creates-sinister-atmosphere
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That sibilance only creates a sinister atmosphere."@en ;
  curric:correction "Sibilance can also create a soothing atmosphere."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682865Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-notice-theme-oppression-migr
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may notice the theme of oppression in ‘The Émigrée’ due to the mention of war, but not notice this in 'Checking Out Me History'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """'Checking Out Me History' explores how Agard presents colonisation and its effects as oppressive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-refers-historical-facts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That context refers just to historical facts."@en ;
  curric:correction """Think about the 'big ideas' in the text and what has influenced and informed these. This all comes under the umbrella of context."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682977Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-general-statement-text-introduction-fact
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The general statement about the text in the introduction can be any fact you know about it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The general statement, the first sentence of your introduction, should still connect to the essay question."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682991Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-utterson-lawyer-man-great-curiosity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Utterson, as a lawyer, is a man of great curiosity and honour."@en ;
  curric:correction """Utterson is both curious for the truth, but cautious about ruining the reputation of his peers. This leads to important clues being missed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quotations-essay-require-analysis
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All quotations in an essay require analysis."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some quotations are useful for supporting your argument but do not require detailed analysis. These should embedded directly into pupils' sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683012Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-describe-sounds-scene-merely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """We need to describe sounds in a scene merely to tick off the fact we have used sensory language."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Thinking of scenarios where sound is particularly important can help us to use sound imagery more effectively."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683016Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-audiences-feel-same-macbeths-death
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All audiences will feel the same about Macbeth's death."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that the joy of literature is exploring different responses to the same text. Use LC1 to identify these differences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683025Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-dickens-solely-emphasising
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils think that Dickens is solely emphasising the value of human life."@en ;
  curric:correction """Dickens is also emphasising the importance of what we do with our lives - how we use them to enrich other people's human experience."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683041Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stevenson-replicates-reiterates-common-gothic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Stevenson just replicates or reiterates common gothic conventions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many common gothic conventions are used but subverted too (the setting of Regent's Park subverts gothic settings)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683046Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-different-ideas-equal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students often think that different ideas equal different arguments."@en ;
  curric:correction """Show students our Oak pupils' suggestions. Their suggestions are not different arguments, but different ideas which can form an argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683050Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-focused-summary-requires
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sometimes students think that a focused summary requires analysis of language."@en ;
  curric:correction """Analysis requires you to zoom in and comment in detail about language choices. Why might this not be useful for a summary, where the aim is to be succinct and give a brief overview of a text?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683055Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-feel-their-viewpoint-needs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may feel that their viewpoint needs to be established in the very first line or so."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Viewpoint can be alluded to in the first few lines and firmly established at the end of the first paragraph or section."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683059Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-victorian-poets-held-same-views
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Victorian poets held the same views and attitudes towards societal issues."@en ;
  curric:correction """Victorian poets had diverse views. Some challenged norms, others reinforced them. Consider each poem's own unique perspective."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683116Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-leave-taking-written-windrush-scandal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Leave Taking' was written about the Windrush scandal."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pinnock explains that she wrote 'Leave Taking' decades before the Windrush scandal, but some themes, like the precarious position of immigrants, happened to resonate with contemporary events when the play was revived."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683121Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-misinterpret-murakamis-semantic-field
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may misinterpret Murakami's semantic field and assume the text is a horror, mystery or thriller story."""@en ;
  curric:correction """If you really break down Murakami's use of semantic field, his word choice is more centered around dynamism of a living organism."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683141Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-proofreading-entails-reading-piece-writing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Proofreading entails reading through a piece of writing once to check for errors."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are a variety of different strategies for proofreading (LC3). Encourage students to use the strategies that work best for them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683145Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-role-comedy-merely-make-people
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The role of comedy is merely to make people laugh."@en ;
  curric:correction "Comedy can be a way of revealing information about characters."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683152Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-dont-realise-dickens-deliberately
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often don't realise that Dickens' deliberately capitalised on a popular genre."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Dickens wanted the novella to become a bestseller, as this would give his message the best chance of reaching as many people as possible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683157Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quotation-supports-your-argument-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any quotation that supports your argument can be used."@en ;
  curric:correction """Select a quotation from learning cycle 1, such as "it wasn't like a man" and ask how much pupils could say about the quotation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683162Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-perspectives-simply-positive-negative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That perspectives are simply positive or negative."@en ;
  curric:correction """Positive and negative can be useful words to initially consider a perspective, but then you must become more nuanced and use specific adjectives to identify feelings and perspectives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683170Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analytical-paragraphs-lead-comparing-writers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Analytical paragraphs should lead by comparing how the writers use language, form and/or structure."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The best comparative analytical writing begins by exploring connections between the key ideas or attitudes in a poem, supported by analysis of how writers use language, form and/or structure to convey these ideas or attitudes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683175Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-sibilance-creates-harsh-sinister
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the use of sibilance creates a harsh, sinister atmosphere."@en ;
  curric:correction """While the hissing sound of sibilance can create a harsh atmosphere, we can also interpret it as a shushing sound that creates a calm atmosphere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683179Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-speaker-rumens-herself
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that the speaker is Rumens herself."@en ;
  curric:correction """Rumens herself did not experience the emigration that the poem describes. She may have written the poem based on her fascination with people and culture. She may have written the poem to appeal to all that have experienced a story of emigration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683186Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-persuasive-issue-based-speeches-maintain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Persuasive, issue based speeches have to maintain a serious tone."@en ;
  curric:correction """Look at Malala's use of humour and anecdote. By engaging the audience in this way she holds their attention enough to make them listen to the serious messages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683193Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-describing-somethings-overall
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that describing something's overall appearance makes a good description."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Description is about making your reader imagine what you are imagining. You have to give really specific details about a person or setting."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-taking-photograph-someones-suffering-effective
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Taking a photograph of someone's suffering is an effective way of showing their suffering to others."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, both Duffy and Ghose reveal the futility of using art as a means of showing their suffering to others."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-erics-guilt-makes-him-fully
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Eric’s guilt makes him fully sympathetic."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eric's actions and narrative can still be challenged. For example, his attempts to downplay his responsibility may show his moral flaws."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683215Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-macbeths-invite-duncan-their-castle
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Macbeths invite Duncan to their castle so they can kill him."@en ;
  curric:correction """King Duncan is honouring the Macbeths by staying with them; he is honouring them because of Macbeth's performance in the recent battle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683256Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-father-christmas-pictured
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students believe that Father Christmas was always pictured wearing red."@en ;
  curric:correction """Victorian depictions of Father Christmas show him wearing green, with a wreath of holly around his head."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683261Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-people-naturally-funny
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students sometimes think that that some people are just naturally funny and that being funny can't be taught."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that humour is a skill that can be developed and practised by using words and phrases deliberately."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683268Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-one-singular-tone
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That a poem must have one singular tone."@en ;
  curric:correction """Often poems express complex emotions. For example, the speaker of 'Lines Written in Early Spring' feels both peace and disquiet at the same time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683273Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysis-led-identification-writers-methods
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Analysis should be led by identification of the writer's methods."@en ;
  curric:correction """Effective comparative analysis should be led by key ideas and then supported by textual evidence and identification of the writer's methods and intentions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683284Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-your-feelings-poem-irrelevant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That your feelings about a poem are irrelevant."@en ;
  curric:correction """How you respond to a poem forms the basis of your argument about a poem - it helps you to understand how a poet has created meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683288Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stevenson-encourages-reader-critical-jekyll
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Stevenson encourages the reader to be critical of Jekyll due to the dual nature inherent inside of him."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stevenson appears to embrace duality, through his rejection of Calvinism and alleged behaviour at university. He is critical of the hypocrisy that arose from those who harboured secrets as a result of duality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683293Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-caseys-playful-tone-makes-light
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Casey's playful tone makes light of class conflict."@en ;
  curric:correction """While Casey uses a playful tone which does lighten the mood of the poem, her use of repeated rhetorical questions foregrounds her more serious message about class prejudice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683297Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-simple-poetry-good-complex-poetry
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That simple poetry is not as good as complex poetry."@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, good poetry creates an emotional response in the reader and evokes a particular image or impression."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683302Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-confuse-language-structural-features
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may confuse language and structural features."@en ;
  curric:correction """Getting into a habit of asking a range of questions interrogating perspective, repetition, beginnings and endings can help students ease into the analysis of structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683311Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-women-completely-powerless-patriarchal-societies
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Women were completely powerless in patriarchal societies."@en ;
  curric:correction "While women's lives were restricted, they were not completely powerless."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683316Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-lady-macbeth-solely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils believe Lady Macbeth is solely responsible for the downfall of her husband."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When discussing Macbeth's intrigue in the prophecies, challenge pupils to question whether Lady Macbeth is responsible at this point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-witches-presented-solely-women-threatening
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The witches are presented solely as women, threatening women but women nonetheless."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Look at the language in Act 1, Scene 3: Banquo and Macbeth see the witches as unnatural, not just strange women."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683325Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-art-meant-beautiful
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Art is always meant to be beautiful."@en ;
  curric:correction """Art can be a means of sparking discussion, representing political views, or addressing problems in society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683329Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-tone-origin-story-simply-nostalgic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The tone of ‘Origin Story’ is simply nostalgic or romantic."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although there are nostalgic and tender elements in the poem, the overall tone is more assertive and self-possessed. This confident tone reflects a deeper purpose: reclaiming identity, celebrating heritage, and asserting authorship over her story."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683334Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-trust-narrator-story-tell-us
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That we can always trust the narrator in a story to tell us the truth about events and people."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Writers will sometimes create unreliable or untrustworthy narrators."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683354Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-writers-attitude-remain-same-throughout
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A writer's attitude will remain the same throughout a non-fiction text."@en ;
  curric:correction """If a writer is recounting an experience then their attitude may change from the beginning to the end of their text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683359Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-writing-number-piece-non-fiction
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Writing down any number in a piece of non-fiction writing is enough to show you know how to use statistics."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Statistics need to be credible. When creating your own statistics, you need to think carefully about how to make them sound believable by giving details like their source, date and data sample size."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683363Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-right-education-same-around-world
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The right to education is the same all around the world."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are many places in the world where girls specifically have to fight for the right to education."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683379Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mother-distance-child-figure-yearns
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """In 'Mother, any distance', the 'child' figure yearns for independence while the parent isn't ready to let them go."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is possible to interpret the poem in this way but it is also possible to infer that the speaker feels nervous about the prospect of their independence, worrying whether they will succeed or "fall"."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683386Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-long-distance-romantic-relationship
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poem is about a long-distance romantic relationship."@en ;
  curric:correction """The relationship between the speaker and the man who sends her letters is ambiguous; it could be platonic, romantic or familial."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683393Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lists-cannot-add-sophistication-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lists cannot add sophistication to your writing."@en ;
  curric:correction "Varying the way we write lists can make our writing more sophisticated."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-critical-means-talk
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that being critical means to talk about the negative aspects of something."""@en ;
  curric:correction "We can be critical by judging something positively or negatively."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683404Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lord-capulet-considers-juliet-dishonoured
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Lord Capulet only considers Juliet to have dishonoured herself through her refusal of the marriage to Paris."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, Lord Capulet also thinks he and the Capulet family are also dishonoured by Juliet's refusal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683409Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-imaginary-blood-lady-macbeths-hands
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The imaginary blood on Lady Macbeth's hands could symbolise Duncan's blood."@en ;
  curric:correction """Symbols represent an idea that doesn't have a physical existence. Guilt is not a physical thing so the object, blood, is used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683413Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-fog-purely-designed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that the fog is purely designed to create an eerie Gothic atmosphere."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Be clear about the symbolic nature of fog. The fact that it can allow for partial visibility."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683418Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-including-impact-text-today-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When including 'the impact of the text today' in your conclusion, you just need to explain why the book is still studied today."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask pupils to 'step outside the text' and think about why themes, characters or moral messages might resonate with readers today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683422Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-scrooge-wicked-character
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think Scrooge is just a wicked character who hates other people, especially the poor."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Scrooge is a product of his environment and exemplifies the attitudes of many Victorian employers and wealthy citizens."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pronoun-example-direct-address
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The pronoun \"you\" is the only example of direct address."@en ;
  curric:correction """Direct address is any way in which a writer directly addresses their audience. This could be a title, name or term."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-need-include-much
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students sometimes think they need to include as much as possible in their argument and support their ideas with overly long quotations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage students to select short and precise quotations to keep their writing concise."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683438Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ending-text-isnt-important-story
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the ending of a text isn't as important as the story itself."@en ;
  curric:correction """The ending of a text defines the story - it offers resolution or poses questions and can impact the way we see characters and the way we interpret the overall meaning of a story."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683443Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-macduff-acts-foil-macbeth-solely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Macduff acts as a foil to Macbeth solely because he is noble and courageous."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask pupils if Macbeth had dealt with his grief/devastation like Macduff would there have been different outcomes?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683456Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-juliet-romeos-love-romeo-juliet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Juliet is Romeo's only love in 'Romeo and Juliet'."@en ;
  curric:correction "Before meeting Juliet, Romeo was in love with Rosaline."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683463Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-ghost-christmas-present
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that the Ghost of Christmas Present is actually holding Plenty's horn."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Dickens carefully clarifies that the torch is "in a shape not unlike Plenty's horn", showing that the torch is not actually Plenty's horn."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683469Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-dickens-harshly-condemns
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students believe that Dickens harshly condemns the wealthy."@en ;
  curric:correction """Dickens only condemns people with money, who choose not to share it with those in need. This is exemplified in the character of Fezziwig."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683474Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-scrooge-selfish-miserable
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that Scrooge is selfish and miserable because he is a wicked person."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Scrooge's miserliness comes from his deep-rooted fear of being poor."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683479Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-recognise-significance-dickens-description
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils do not recognise the significance of Dickens' description of Scrooge's fireplace."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The description contains a multitude of allusions that enhance our understanding of the characters Marley's Ghost and Scrooge."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683483Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-love-poems-contain-ideas-warmth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Love poems always contain ideas of warmth and happiness."@en ;
  curric:correction """Love is not always warm or happy - love poems often reflect the uncertainty, worry, and pain that love can bring people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683492Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-opinions-response-written-texts-equal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All opinions in response to written texts are equal."@en ;
  curric:correction """The best personal responses to texts will evaluate the writer's craft in eliciting that opinion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683512Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-confused-extract-taking-place
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may be confused about when the extract is taking place or what war the extract is about as it references multiple moments of time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The novel opening takes place during the siege of Sarajevo in the 1990s. However, the reference to the aftermath of WW2 is significant in universalising the themes and messages of the novel."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683526Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-use-objects-symbolise-ideas
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may use objects to symbolise ideas but the object may not quite match the idea e.g. violence represented by a flower."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Thinking about the feelings that an object makes us feel might help us to decide whether it will be an appropriate symbolic object."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683531Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romeo-said-love-love-consistent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Romeo is often said to be 'in love with love' and this is consistent throughout the play."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In Act 3, Scene 1, Romeo expresses negative feelings towards the concept of being in love."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683542Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lady-macbeth-doesnt-value-loyalty
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lady Macbeth doesn't value loyalty."@en ;
  curric:correction """Lady Macbeth does value loyalty, but loyalty to herself and her ambitions, not the chivalric code."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683556Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-tend-struggle-understand-scrooge
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students tend to struggle to understand how Scrooge has metaphorically fathered Ignorance and Want."""@en ;
  curric:correction """By being ignorant, Scrooge has neglected his social responsibility and nurtured inequality and injustice - the two children represent this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683563Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-stave-4-scrooge
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that, in Stave 4, Scrooge is frightened of dying."@en ;
  curric:correction """Scrooge is not frightened of death. He is frightened of dying without leaving a legacy because he has not contributed anything to society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683567Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-open-letters-written
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may believe that open letters have to be written to those in powerful positions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are open letters on a wide range of topics and niches. All that an open letter requires is a strong feeling about something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683572Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-irony-same-thing-coincidence
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That irony is the same thing as a coincidence."@en ;
  curric:correction """Irony is a contrast between expectations and reality whereas coincidence involves a great deal of luck, or chance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683577Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shelleys-poem-presents-purely-positive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Shelley's poem presents a purely positive view of love."@en ;
  curric:correction """Interspersed among his speaker's overblown philosophical descriptions focused around the beauty of natural symmetry, it's possible to read an element of frustration that the speaker's feelings of desire are unrequited."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-form-structure-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Form and structure are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Form deals with the 'poetic rules' that govern a poem and helps us to categorise it along with other similar poems whereas structure deals with how the ideas in the poem are ordered and organised."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683592Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-material-possessions-dont-matter
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That material possessions don't matter."@en ;
  curric:correction """While material possessions can be replaced, nevertheless they do provide a sense of safety and comfort for us."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683597Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-titles-shouldnt-form-part-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That titles shouldn't form a part of your analysis."@en ;
  curric:correction """The title forms our first impression of the poem and therefore is a rich area for analysis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683602Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysing-language-features-enough
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Analysing language features is enough."@en ;
  curric:correction """The best analysis - with the richest commentary - will also spend time focusing on structural decisions a writer makes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683619Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-cant-used-thesis-statement
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Context can't be used in a thesis statement. It must be saved for main body paragraphs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Including context in a thesis statement is a powerful way to start an essay. It shows you understand the writer's intentions with their work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683627Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-writers-create-entirely-original-characters
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Writers always create entirely original characters, and using similar character types or archetypes makes a story unoriginal."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Archetypes explore universal themes, evolving with context. Writers reshape them, making characters unique while keeping familiar depth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683631Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-work-text-chronologically-selecting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils must work through the text chronologically when selecting supporting evidence."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Pupils need to think of the logical order they should analyse evidence from the text - which section of the novella is strongest at proving their topic sentence?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683638Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparative-paragraphs-focus-differences
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Comparative paragraphs should only focus on differences."@en ;
  curric:correction """The most effective comparisons look for subtle differences within larger similarities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-because-wordsworth-loved
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that because Wordsworth loved nature, he couldn't be frightened of it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Wordsworth respected and loved nature - he understood the sheer size and power of nature versus his own existence. His own insignificance in the face of such astonishing and breath-taking views arguably made him feel slightly fearful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683652Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-need-zoom-word
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that they need to 'zoom in' on every word when analysing a quotation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Often, it can be useful to discuss the 'bigger' method that the poet is using e.g. their use of personification. By thinking about bigger methods, the students may be more focused on the themes of the poem and the poet's intentions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683657Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shouldnt-edit-rewrite-your-writing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you shouldn't edit and rewrite your writing as you are doing it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Often it's very effective to rewrite your work as you go so that you can continually craft an effective idea and ensure you are creating a cohesive piece."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683696Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-say-your-character-isnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That you just need to say that your character isn't human to create an artifical voice."""@en ;
  curric:correction """To create an artificial voice, you want to consider how your character would describe themselves, their surroundings, and their interactions in a way that shows they are not human."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683700Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-setting-used-solely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students sometimes think that setting is used solely to create atmosphere."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage students to see Stevenson's use of setting as figurative as well as literal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-try-include-much-knowledge
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students try to include as much knowledge as possible in their responses."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage students to be selective in their choice of ideas and to explain their choices."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683717Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-associate-war-poetry-soldiers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may associate war poetry with soldiers of the first world war and not consider other perspectives."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many other people were affected by war in less obvious ways than the soldiers themselves."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-way-evaluate-write
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that they only way to evaluate is to write whether they 'agree' or 'disagree' with something."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In Learning Cycle 2, students learn that they can phrase and signpost their evaluations in a more sophisticated way, directly commenting on the writer's craft with evaluative adverbs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683727Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-macbeth-characteristics-tragic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils think Macbeth has all of the characteristics of a tragic hero."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use learning cycle 2 to draw out a debate about whether Macbeth actually learnt a lesson, highlighting where pupils may not agree."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683732Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-murder-banquo-fleance-attempted-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The murder of Banquo and Fleance (attempted) is the same as the murders that have preceded it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Macbeth doesn't tell Lady Macbeth his plan, he hires murderers rather than doing it himself, and Fleance is a child."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683737Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-compare-methods-writers-use-comparing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You can only compare methods that both writers use when comparing non-fiction texts."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It can be very effective to compare why one writer might choose to use a certain method while another writer may choose not to use it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683743Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-conflict-occurs-one-person-least
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Conflict always occurs between one person and at least one other person."@en ;
  curric:correction """Conflict can be within someone's own mind (inner conflict) and it doesn't always have to involve people at all. Powerful ideas or forces can be in conflict with one another too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-society-considered-childhood-space-play
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That society has always considered childhood as a space for play and exploration."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Before the Enlightenment, children were generally considered small versions of adults."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683754Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plot-important-part-narrative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Plot is the most important part of a narrative."@en ;
  curric:correction """Voice is equally important to plot when writing a narrative. Ask students: if there was a resolution to the story but no distinct voice, how would the story change? Would it be effective, enjoyable?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683764Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lord-capulet-tybalt-share-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lord Capulet and Tybalt share the same views on all the Montagues."@en ;
  curric:correction """While Lord Capulet wishes to join the fight in Act 1, Scene 1, he encourages Tybalt to leave Romeo alone at the Caplulet ball."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-novellas-title-chosen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think the novella's title was chosen simply to reflect the festive period it covers."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The title is more symbolic of Dickens' intentions - he intended for the message from this text to be spread far and wide, much like a carol."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ww1-poets-portrayed-dying-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "WW1 poets portrayed dying for their country as glorious."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some WW1 poets did portray it as glorious, poets such as Wilfred Owen depicted the horrors and futility of the war."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-planning-takes-much-time-isnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Planning takes too much time and isn’t worth it when writing an essay."@en ;
  curric:correction """Planning saves time overall. It helps you organise your ideas, stay focused, and write more clearly and effectively, making your essay stronger and easier to complete."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683788Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparing-language-best-way-compare
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That comparing language is the best way to compare poems."@en ;
  curric:correction """As well as comparing the language, you can also compare the use of form, structure and voice in poems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683793Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sheilas-transformation-guarantees-societal-change
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sheila's transformation guarantees societal change."@en ;
  curric:correction """While her growth is significant, it doesn't ensure broader social progress, as societal norms and traditions play a major role."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683810Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-education-ever-positive-power
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Education is only ever a positive power."@en ;
  curric:correction """Consider Pinnock's words about her parents' generation and why and how education can be used as a tool of oppression."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683923Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-romantic-view-love-abstract
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """This poem is only about a Romantic view of love (from an abstract, philosophical perspective)."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem appears to have an ulterior motive. Shelley uses language, form and structure to subtly persuade the listener to enter into a romantic relationship with him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683928Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-starting-vivid-description-characters-pain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Starting with a vivid description of the character's pain is a great way to hook a reader."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While beginning with a vivid description of pain can add an element of shock, it often doesn't leave the reader anywhere to go emotionally. It might be more effective to leave vivid descriptions of pain for the climax of a text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683932Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-narrative-written-first-person-perspective
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A narrative written in the first person perspective conveys the writer's voice."@en ;
  curric:correction """A narrative written in the first person perspective does not necessarily reflect the writer's voice but a construct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683956Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-manipulate-time-one-way-narrative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "We can only manipulate time in one way in a narrative."@en ;
  curric:correction """When we know the effect that we want our flashbacks and flashforwards to have, we can use both."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683963Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-paris-unimportant-plot-device-romeo
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Paris is an unimportant plot device in 'Romeo and Juliet'."@en ;
  curric:correction """Paris' interactions with Lord Capulet and Juliet arguably reveal contemporary stereotypes of relationships between men and women."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683968Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enid-other-immigrants-came-britain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Enid and other immigrants came to Britain fully aware of the challenges and were prepared for discrimination."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Pinnock explains that many, like Enid, saw themselves as British subjects and expected a “homecoming”, so the hostility and racism they faced were a shock."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683972Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-dickens-offers-condemnation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students believe that Dickens only offers a condemnation of the immorality exhibited by Mrs. Dilber."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Dickens, though he doesn't condone the character's behaviour, does empathise with her, and illustrates that she is the product of injustice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683977Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-essay-completed-its-worth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once an essay is completed it's not worth thinking about again."@en ;
  curric:correction """How does rewriting support the writing of future responses? Consider the strategies, tips and phrases explored. Revisiting our own essays can make feedback become really personalised and allow you to work and focus on your own targets."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poems-use-first-person-persepctive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Both poems use a first-person persepctive and therefore express similar attitudes towards love and identity."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While both use first-person perspective, ‘Catrin’ shows intense, ongoing maternal love, and ‘Origin Story’ reflects on a past, fragile romantic love. The attitudes differ because one is direct and personal, the other reflective and shaped by memory."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683992Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mrs-birlings-interrogation-shows-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mrs. Birling’s interrogation shows her changing attitude towards responsibility."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Mrs. Birling has some revelations about her family towards the end of Act 2, her attitude remains unchanged at the end of the play. She stubbornly refuses to accept any responsibility, reinforcing her commitment to class prejudices."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684031Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comments-writers-intentions-choices-absolute
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any comments about a writer's intentions or choices must be absolute."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although we may never know for certain, we can use clues like contextual information to develop ideas around intentions and choices. We can also use tentative language to put forward our ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684035Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-form-poem-author-choose-means
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The form of poem an author might choose means little to the message"@en ;
  curric:correction """Poets pick their forms carefully, as we can see in 'Ozymandias' even the slight tweaking of form can impact the reading of the poem and its meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684040Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-women-took-passive-role-relationships
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That women always took a passive role in relationships in the Elizabethan era."@en ;
  curric:correction "Arguably, Juliet takes an active role in her relationship with Romeo."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romeo-juliets-first-conversation-exclusively
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That Romeo and Juliet's first conversation exclusively focuses on the physicality of their love."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While Romeo and Juliet's first conversation contains many references to "lips" and "palms", the religious imagery also implies their spiritual connection."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684049Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysis-include-language-focus-especially
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Analysis can only include a language focus, especially single word analysis."@en ;
  curric:correction """You should analyse a range of writer's methods; this analysis should support your thesis or topic sentence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684056Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-figurative-language-fictional-writing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can only use figurative language in fictional writing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Non-fiction writers, just like fiction writers, are trying to create interesting, original and compelling ideas that their readers will remember, enjoy and learn from."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684060Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-writing-extended-piece-fiction-non
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When writing an extended piece of fiction or non-fiction, you should include every single method you know."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Different texts are read for different reasons and by different audiences. It is your job, as the writer, to consider which are the best methods for your particular text. Just because you know how to use a method, doesn't mean you have to include it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684067Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-linguistic-devices-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that linguistic devices should be used as often as possible."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage them to use linguistic devices judiciously. Overuse can be as as much of a problem as underuse."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684072Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-wife-receives-two
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often think that the wife receives two letters."@en ;
  curric:correction """The wife receives a telegram and a letter. Both the irony and the tragedy are in the fact that, due to the quick nature of telegrams, the wife receives news of her husband's death before she receives his letter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684077Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-entirely-autobiographical-written-clarkes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """This poem is entirely autobiographical, written about Clarke's experiences of motherhood."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem was written just after the birth of Clarke's fist daughter so does reflect on her experiences of motherhood but the later scenes of a older child playing out are necessarily fictional."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684088Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-narratives-follow-traditional-story-arc
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All narratives have to follow the traditional story arc and have a chronological order for them to make sense."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Short stories often have to manipulate the traditional story structure to be engaging from the very beginning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-fail-consider-symbolic-importance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often fail to consider the symbolic importance of Duncan and, in particular, Malcolm in the play."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask pupils what the moral message of the play would be if Malcolm did not end the play as king."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684131Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-macbeth-solely-worried-banquo-fleance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Macbeth is solely worried about Banquo and Fleance in this scene."@en ;
  curric:correction """Macbeth's focus is Banquo and his son, but his language reveals his worries about the regicide, his soul and his immediate future."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684135Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysing-pupils-need-clear-viewpoint
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "When analysing, all pupils need is a clear viewpoint."@en ;
  curric:correction """A clear viewpoint is important, but adding nuance will improve the quality of pupil responses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684142Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-whether-dr-lanyon-foil-dr
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Whether Dr. Lanyon being a foil for Dr. Jekyll is a straightforward answer."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whether Lanyon is a foil for Jekyll is debatable. They have clear differences (e.g. scientific views) but similarities too (curiosity)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684153Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-semicolons-used-join-two-clauses
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Semicolons can be used to join any two clauses of any length."@en ;
  curric:correction """The clauses joined by a semicolon must be both be independent clauses (which means they make sense of their own) and should be linked in terms of their subject matter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684158Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hyperbole-exaggeration-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Hyperbole and exaggeration are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Exaggeration is a broad term for overstating something beyond the truth, while hyperbole is a specific type of exaggeration used deliberately for emphasis or effect, often in a dramatic or humorous way."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684162Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-show-tell-key
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that they should show or tell the key details of a story immediately."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage them to think about mysteries and thrillers which keep the identify of the villain secret."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-foreshadowing-used-upcoming
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think foreshadowing can only be used for upcoming events of a negative nature."""@en ;
  curric:correction """If pupils want to hint at positive memory to come, foreshadowing can also be used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684171Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-two-poets-use-same-technique
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "When two poets use the same technique then they have the same intended outcome."@en ;
  curric:correction """Poetic techniques can be interpreted in a number of different ways, so you can't assume that if a second poet uses the same technique as a first then it will have the same meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684182Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-looking-other-essays-cheating-copying
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Looking at other essays is cheating or copying."@en ;
  curric:correction """Working with model responses helps develop your critical skills in order to evaluate your own work. Using and adapting others' ideas is a great thing to do!"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684187Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-planning-note-form
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All planning should be in note form."@en ;
  curric:correction """Foundations of your essay - thesis and topic sentences - should be written in full so you know they are powerful, precise and purposeful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684255Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-its-best-give-reader-backstory
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It's best to give the reader all of the backstory at the start of a novel so that they understand the context of the events."""@en ;
  curric:correction """By feeding information to the audience slowly, it arguably builds discomfort in the reader and creates an unsettling environment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684262Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-eva-smith-doesnt-dialogue-therefore
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Eva Smith doesn’t have dialogue and therefore she can’t be analysed in depth."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eva’s lack of dialogue actually makes her more powerful to analyse. Her silence and absence force the audience to focus on how others speak about her."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684271Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-come-new-ideas
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think they have to come up with new ideas for each essay question they attempt."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Highlight similarities between the modelled plan on 'hypocrisy' and their own ideas relationing to 'duality'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684276Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-similes-metaphors-interchangeable
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That similes and metaphors are interchangeable."@en ;
  curric:correction """Similes and metaphors are conceptually different since, in a simile, one thing does not become another while in a metaphor they do become each other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684280Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-point-talking-minor-characters-play
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There is no point talking about the minor characters in a play - they are not important."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Each character, no matter how seemingly insignificant, is crafted by the writer and placed in the text for a specific purpose. It is your job to consider what their purpose is."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684285Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-peoples-attitudes-war-stagnant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "People's attitudes to war are stagnant."@en ;
  curric:correction """Wilfred Owen's attitude towards war changed after he enlisted. His poetry explores this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684319Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-blake-opposed-education
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Blake is opposed to all education."@en ;
  curric:correction """Blake critiques oppressive institutions, not education itself, reflecting Romanticism's focus on freedom and natural growth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684324Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-play-past-historical-events
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The play is only about the past or historical events."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pinnock emphasises that the play connects past and present. It explores immigrant experiences, cultural identity, and family relationships, showing issues that are still relevant today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684359Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-proofreading-your-work-important-plan
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Proofreading your work is not important if you plan it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Proofreading is equally important as planning. In pressured writing environments, we can easily make mistakes that we are not aware of."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684388Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-justice-exclusively-linked-legal-punishment
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Justice is exclusively linked to legal punishment."@en ;
  curric:correction """In 'An Inspector Calls', Priestley challenges the idea that justice is solely legal. He presents moral and psychological punishment, showing that guilt and self-reflection drive real change, not just legal consequences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684392Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-differences-need-large
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students often think that differences need to be large when comparing texts."@en ;
  curric:correction "Encourage them to look for subtle differences."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684397Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-argument-disagreement-something-confrontational
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "An argument is a disagreement and something which is confrontational."@en ;
  curric:correction """In an article, an argument is a reason or set of reasons given in support of an idea, action or theory that you give the reader in order to convince them that your idea is correct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684402Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sublime-refers-something-solely-positive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The 'sublime' refers to something solely positive."@en ;
  curric:correction """While the 'sublime' suggests a reverence and awe for something, it also implies ideas of feeling insignificant and overwhelmed by it which therefore adds the idea of terror or fear."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684413Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-talk-marley-marleys-ghost
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often talk about Marley and Marley's Ghost as if they are the exact same character."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Marley in life held very different beliefs from Marley's ghost; his ghost acts as Scrooge's redeemer and represents something different."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-travel-writing-needs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may think that travel writing needs to be about far away places."@en ;
  curric:correction """Draw their attention to the social messages implied in the titles 'Down and Out in Paris and London' and 'Travels with Charley: In Search of America'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684426Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-exposure-depicts-power-nature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Exposure' only depicts the power of nature."@en ;
  curric:correction """If we look critically, we can identify how Owen criticises and rejects powerful ideas and institutions, like other poets from the anthology."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poems-based-firsthand-experience-war
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Both poems are based on a firsthand experience of war."@en ;
  curric:correction """Only 'Exposure' is based on firsthand experience since Owen was serving as a WWI British soldier while writing. Satyamurti's poem wasn't based on any one particular person, event or conflict."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-benjamin-zephaniah-wrote-exaggerated-phonetic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Benjamin Zephaniah wrote in an exaggerated phonetic way to represent the accent of the speaker."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Zephaniah was a dub poet which meant that he performed his work aloud. This phonetic spelling should be viewed more as a transcription of Zephaniah's own cultural patois."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-words-exchanged-characters-effective-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The words exchanged between characters are the most effective way to convey the relationship between them."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Often, the most effective dialogue comes from considering body language and the balance of the lines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684445Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-believes-control-our-life
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That everyone believes we all have control over our life and decisions."@en ;
  curric:correction """If you believe in fate, then you believe that our life is predetermined and our decisions ultimately don't matter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684449Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-macbeth-next-line-throne
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Macbeth is next in line to the throne."@en ;
  curric:correction """Malcolm has been named Duncan's heir. However, he flees to England and thus Macbeth is crowned King."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684461Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-liminal-spaces-things-unnerving-mysterious
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Liminal spaces are things that are unnerving in a mysterious way."@en ;
  curric:correction """Liminal spaces often do create a unnerving tone, but this is due to them being the boundary to two opposing states."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684494Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-genre-novella-solely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils think the genre of this novella is solely Gothic fiction."@en ;
  curric:correction """Even without the presence of a detective character, the use of concealment and a carefully crafted mystery make this detective fiction too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mr-utterson-example-respectable-victorian
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mr. Utterson is an example of a respectable, Victorian gentleman."@en ;
  curric:correction """The reality is more complex. Utterson seems more concerned with protecting the reputation of Jekyll than pursuing any real justice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684505Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-writing-begin-beginning
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that all writing should begin at the beginning and move through the middle to the end."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage them to think about how stories, especially films, often start with an exciting scene."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684510Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-speaker-mourning-loss-summer
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "This poem is about a speaker who is mourning the loss of summer."@en ;
  curric:correction """The poem can also be read as a metaphor for the passing of time. Whilst there are moments which feel mournful in the poem, there is a sense of hope and encouragement."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684515Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-recognise-poem-metaphor-human
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may not recognise that this poem is a metaphor for human mortality and the approach of death."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Keats wrote this poem after he had been diagnosed with tuberculosis. Perhaps this poem was his way of accepting his own approaching death."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684524Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-irregular-structure-creates-sense
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Using an irregular structure always creates a sense of freedom."@en ;
  curric:correction """While it can create a sense of freedom, an irregular structure can also create ideas of unpredictability and uncertainty."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684535Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparison-involves-spotting-differences-poems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That comparison involves spotting the differences between poems."@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, the best comparisons are where there is an exploration of subtle differences within similarities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684540Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-bluebeard-allusion-represents-danger-violence
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The \"Bluebeard\" allusion represents only danger and violence in childhood."@en ;
  curric:correction """The allusion reflects both the danger and the intense, unrestrained joy of childhood, where pleasure feels almost forbidden."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684544Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-because-society-religious
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that, because society was very religious in the 18th century, that Blake must have been a devout Christian too."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Blake was extremely opposed to mass worship and hated the fact that religion was allied with the Government - he felt this gave institutions the ability to control and oppress people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-bolt-added-onto-end
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Context is a bolt-on and can just be added onto the end of a paragraph."@en ;
  curric:correction "Context should be a considered and interwoven part of any essay."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684560Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-understand-argument-build-complexity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students do not understand that an argument should build in complexity."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students should consider the structure of their argument. Which ideas need to come first in order to foreground other ideas?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684565Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-writers-method-similes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that the writer's method is just similes/metaphors etc."@en ;
  curric:correction """The writer's method is anything that they do consciously - it's any conscious choice that they make."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-novel-entirely-secrets
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think the novel is entirely about secrets."@en ;
  curric:correction "Remind them how often Hyde is observed committing crimes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-macbeth-his-wife
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils assume Macbeth and his wife have never had children."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils about Lady Macbeth's "I have given suck" (1.7). Explore the idea that the Macbeths may have had a child die in infancy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684593Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-idyllic-settings-stay-same-forever
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That idyllic settings stay the same forever."@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, Landon's 'Captain Cook (To My Brother)' suggests that an idyllic place does not last forever."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-take-time-plan-properly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students do not take the time to plan properly before writing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Not taking the time to plan a response properly makes your argument less concise and less coherent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684602Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dream-caused-utterson-state-distress
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the dream is only caused by Utterson being in a state of distress."@en ;
  curric:correction "Unpick the details of the dream to show the parallels with the plot."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rewording-summarising-main-points-question
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Rewording or summarising the main points of a question will lead to a developed response."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A nuanced response goes beyond rewording the question. It requires you to engage deeply with the text, offering detailed analysis and considering multiple layers of meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dystopian-voices-fit-archetype-e
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Dystopian voices have to fit the archetype (e.g. rebellious, overly critical) in order to be compelling."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ishiguro subtly crafts his voices to allow the reader to reflect on their own world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684620Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-topic-sentence-straight
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students believe that the topic sentence has to be a straight-forward statement of opinion."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The topic sentence, like any other part of their writing, can be written creatively, forcing the reader to infer the writer's opinion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684624Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-considering-poem-stronger-emotional-reaction
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That considering which poem you have a stronger emotional reaction to is not worthwhile."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Comparing your personal responses to poems can help you to see how the poet has managed to create meaning and mood through their writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-three-poems-convey-negative-view
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All three poems convey a negative view of romantic relationships."@en ;
  curric:correction """All three poems begin by conveying a negative view of romantic relationships. This continues throughout 'Neutral Tones' and 'When We Two Parted' however 'Winter Swans' undergoes a shift to a hopeful tone by the end as the couple are unified."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684639Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysis-focus-bride
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Analysis should focus on the bride."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although there is lots to say about the bride - and her treatment in the relationship - the farmer also presents a rich source of analysis through his often contradictory actions throughout the poem (explored in the written task in Learning Cycle 2)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-embed-their-quotations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students do not embed their quotations."@en ;
  curric:correction """If students don't embed their quotations, the response is not as concise as it could be. Being concise makes your response sophisticated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-because-old-book
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might think that because this is an 'old book', it might not still bear a relevant message."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The novella is a timeless classic because its message is universal. As long as there is injustice in the world, the text remains relevant."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mrs-birling-woman-therefore-automatically
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mrs Birling is a woman and therefore she automatically shares the same struggles as Eva Smith."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While both are women, Mrs Birling's high class gives her power to uphold societal norms, whereas Eva, from a lower class, is oppressed by them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684660Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-planning-essay-means-listing-points
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Planning an essay just means listing points I want to cover and then writing a draft straight away."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst this can work, clearly understanding your argument, structuring your ideas, and deciding what evidence or quotations to use before you start writing can be much more efficient and effective."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684664Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thesis-statements-general
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Thesis statements have to be very general."@en ;
  curric:correction """Thesis statements can be specific, but they should offer opportunity to consider different interpretations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-books-irrelevant-them-their-lives
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Books are irrelevant to them and their lives."@en ;
  curric:correction """Books are one way of sharing stories - stories have always been part of human history as they are a way of forming connections and understanding the world around us."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-labeling-literary-features-like-metaphor
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Labeling literary features like "metaphor" or "imagery" is enough to demonstrate analysis."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Feature spotting is not analysis. You need to explain how the writer's choices create different meanings and link to the writer's intention and wider themes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684736Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dr-jekyll-enjoys-experience-mr
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Dr. Jekyll enjoys the experience of being Mr. Hyde."@en ;
  curric:correction "Encourage students to notice the different ways that Dr. Jekyll has declined."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684745Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-end-chapter-8-implies-jekyll
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The end of Chapter 8 implies Jekyll regretted creating Hyde."@en ;
  curric:correction """Jekyll is a very complex character, his actions need to be explored with nuance. The best responses will consider Jekyll's joy and regret."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-forgiveness-personal-choice
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That forgiveness is always a personal choice."@en ;
  curric:correction "Sometimes people feel societal pressure to forgive someone."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684754Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-benvolio-peaceful-character-romeo-juliet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Benvolio is a peaceful character in 'Romeo and Juliet'."@en ;
  curric:correction """While Benvolio calls for peace, he engages in violence when he thinks it is necessary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romeo-impulsive-juliet-shakespeares-romeo
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Romeo is more impulsive than Juliet in Shakespeare's 'Romeo and Juliet'."@en ;
  curric:correction "Arguably, Juliet's actions are also impulsive."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-byron-portrays-assyrians-evil-predators
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Byron portrays the Assyrians as evil predators because this was what he believed they were like."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, we can't know Byron's feelings on this matter. It's more likely that he portrays the Assyrians in this way to emphasise the power of God when he is able to easily decimate such a formidable enemy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684792Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-look-differences-poems-comparative-response
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That you should only look for differences between poems in a comparative response."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A comparative response involves analysing and exploring the similarities and differences in how two poems present an idea or concept."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684796Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sensory-imagery-equally-effective
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All sensory imagery is equally effective."@en ;
  curric:correction """The best sensory imagery employs precise language to achieve specific atmospheres."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684800Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-elizabethan-england-share-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That people in Elizabethan England share the same ideas about religion as we do in modern society."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Religion was central to people's lives in Elizabethan England in a way that it is not in modern society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-macbeth-actually-sees-dagger
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Macbeth actually sees a dagger."@en ;
  curric:correction """Shakespeare signals the dagger is a hallucination, and that Macbeth is aware it is a hallucination too: 'a dagger of the mind'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684812Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-banquos-ghost-definitely-figment-macbeths
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Banquo's ghost is definitely a figment of Macbeth's imagination."@en ;
  curric:correction """It's up to directors whether Banquo's ghost should appear on stage; an actor could play this part, or Macbeth could be scared of nothing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684816Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-concluding-sentences-same-conclusions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Concluding sentences are the same as conclusions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Concluding sentences conclude a single paragraph. Conclusions come at the end of a full essay."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684823Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-tend-bolt-irrelevant-context
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students tend to 'bolt' irrelevant context onto the end of analytical paragraphs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Context should be integrated into students' responses and should enhance or support their arguments."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684827Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speech-approached-like-other-written
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A speech should be approached like any other written text."@en ;
  curric:correction """Speeches should be approached in a very different way to other types of written text as they are designed to be spoken aloud. Long sentences, for example, should avoided since they are difficult for audiences to follow when heard aloud."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684836Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-websites-dont-need-engaging-provide
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Websites don't need to be engaging if they only provide information."@en ;
  curric:correction """What is the purpose of a website? If you want people to read the information, how are you going to engage your reader?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684841Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-poem-written-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students might think that this poem was written from one lover to another."@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem is about Lord Byron's first encounter with his cousin's wife - as far as we know, he doesn't interact with her or pursue her - he merely observes her beauty from afar."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684861Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-frogs-literally-attacking
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that the frogs are literally attacking the speaker."@en ;
  curric:correction """The description in the poem of the frogs as an army is the speaker's perception of the frogs - it is how he imagines them to be behaving."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684865Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-types-negative-feelings-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That all types of negative feelings are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are nuances within negativity - some negative emotions might stem from fear, anger, jealousy or uncertainty."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-half-caste-word-used-describe
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """'Half-caste' is a word used to describe people whose parents have different racial or cultural backgrounds."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This is a historical term and is now considered inappropriate and disrespectful to use. Instead, we may use terms such as 'mixed race' or 'dual heritage' to discuss someone's cultural or racial background."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romantic-poetry-love
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Romantic poetry is always about love."@en ;
  curric:correction """Romantic and romantic are two different words. The former, Romantic, refers to a cultural and artistic movement in the 1700-1800s whereas the latter, romantic, means 'linked to love and relationships'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enemy-soldier-similar-person-speaker
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The 'enemy' soldier was a similar person to the speaker - he did a similar job and was of a similar social status."""@en ;
  curric:correction """We only learn about the 'enemy' soldier through the speaker's perspective. In stanza 4, the speaker infers what the man's life was like and, in turn, reveals a lot about his life and motivations for joining the army."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684885Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-doesnt-matter-two-poems-choose
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It doesn't matter which two poems you choose to compare as all of them can be compared with each other."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In theory, you can compare any two poems from the anthology however it's important to remember that some have more connections than others. You should aim to select two poems with a range of connections to avoid tenuous links."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684890Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-talking-why-like-something-good
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Talking about why you like something is a good topic for a speech."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although it is important to choose something that interests you, you need to ensure the topic that you choose will enable you to present some complex ideas and use sophisticated vocabulary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-knowing-brownings-married-other-important
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Knowing that the Brownings were married to each other is an important piece of contextual information."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although it is relevant to know they were married, it is in linking their own unconventional marriage to the subversive presentation of love and relationships in their poems that the best contextual points can be found."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684922Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-assume-writing-poet-wants
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may assume that writing about how the poet wants the reader to feel is enough when writing about intent."""@en ;
  curric:correction """To add sophistication and criticality to writing, evaluative verbs can be very effective when discussing the writer's intent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684928Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stories-unambiguously-plotted-freytags-pyramid
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All stories can be unambiguously plotted on a Freytag's Pyramid. It is clear which element is which."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Complex stories, like Jekyll and Hyde, are open to interpretation as to how each element can be plotted on the pyramid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-macbeth-tyrannical-ruler-enjoys-his
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Macbeth is a tyrannical ruler, and enjoys his tyranny."@en ;
  curric:correction """Macbeth is a tyrant, but doesn't enjoy his reign. He is also self-aware: "I am in blood Stepp'd so far" or calling the witches "the worst"."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684955Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plan-isnt-useful-revision-tool
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A plan isn't a useful revision tool."@en ;
  curric:correction """Creating a plan, and revisiting it, is an excellent way to revise. It can be quicker than writing a full essay, but still requires you to think about a particular essay question and your argument in response to it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684962Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-novel-gothic-typical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may think that the novel is Gothic in the typical sense."@en ;
  curric:correction """Be clear about subversion and how it works in the novella. Although Stevenson uses some Gothic elements they are not always used in the typical way for the genre."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684967Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-refuting-counter-arguments-enough-create
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Refuting counter-arguments is enough to create an impact."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although it is good practice to refute counter-arguments, we can also use language devices when we do so to make them even more powerful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684971Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-language-structure-informative-website-unexciting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The language and structure of an informative website is always unexciting and dull."""@en ;
  curric:correction """What is the best way to remember information? Are you more likely to remember if it is presented in an interesting and engaging way? Informative websites still need to engage their audience."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-used-writing-their-memories
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might be used to writing their memories as a stream of consciousness, without stopping to consider craft."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Writing memories as a stream of consciousness is a good place to start. However, once one thinks about publishing work, editing and conscious crafting is necessary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684980Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-depicts-nothing-physical-journey
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poem depicts nothing more than a physical journey across a lake."@en ;
  curric:correction """The poem's physical journey symbolises a spiritual journey and the ''growth'' of Wordsworth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684985Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-want-focus-differences-comparisons
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you only want to focus on differences in comparisons."@en ;
  curric:correction """When comparing poems, you want to begin by showing their overarching similarity and then explore the subtle differences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684989Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analytical-paragraphs-led-identification-writers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Analytical paragraphs should be led by identification of writer's methods."@en ;
  curric:correction """An effective analytical response avoids 'feature-spotting'. Paragraphs should be led with a comparison of key ideas in each poem, followed by a detailed analysis of how the writers use methods to convey these ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684994Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-structural-choices-happen-accidentally
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That structural choices happen accidentally."@en ;
  curric:correction """Structural choices are consciously made by the poet in order to influence the meaning of the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-once-put-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that once they have put their pen down and stopped writing, that they have finished."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Students should think of their first attempt as simply a first draft. The second redraft is their chance to fine tune their argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685014Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-characters-hypocritical-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think all the characters are hypocritical because they are all keeping secrets."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Keep drawing their attention back to the keywords and their definitions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-anaphora-refrain-same-types-repetition
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Anaphora and refrain are the same. They are both types of repetition."@en ;
  curric:correction """While both anaphora and a refrain are both types of repetition, they function differently. Anaphora occurs when the beginning of a sentence is repeated, whereas a refrain when a key idea is repeated throughout a text, like a chorus in a song."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685025Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-figurative-language-such-similes-belongs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Figurative language such as similes belongs in fictional writing rather than non-fiction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Non-fiction writing is all about informing, persuading or educating the reader and therefore similes can be a very useful device to explain ideas to the reader."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685030Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysing-text-individual-exercise
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Analysing a text is an individual exercise."@en ;
  curric:correction """Having discussions around a text can help us build on our ideas and reconsider different ways of interpreting the text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685035Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-good-vs-evil-easy-recognise
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That good vs. evil is easy to recognise in characters when reading stories or watching plays."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In tragedies, sometimes a character can embody both good and evil or there could be different perceptions of a character's nature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685040Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-scrooge-raising-bobs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some students might think that Scrooge raising Bob's wage is an act of charity or generosity."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Scrooge never paid Bob fairly to begin with. He is therefore not doing him a favour by raising his wage, but simply doing the decent thing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685046Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-effective-analysis-writing-explores-attitudes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Effective analysis writing explores the attitudes in the first text and then, in another paragraph, explores the attitudes in the second text."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The most effective comparative analysis writing will weave comparisons of both texts together. The response will ideally move between examples from each text, weighing up and evaluating the writer's choices in each."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685051Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lines-9-16-poem-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Lines 9-16 of the poem use abstract imagery to convey the moment of the birth in the hospital room."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While this is one way of interpreting these lines, others have argued the abstract images could reflect society's unfair expectations of mothers and the nature of the developing maternal relationship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685060Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lady-macbeth-doesnt-think-guilt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lady Macbeth doesn't think guilt is a powerful emotion."@en ;
  curric:correction """Lady Macbeth acknowledges that guilt can make people 'mad' or 'brainsickly' in 2.2. This is why she tries to reject the emotion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685069Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-assume-need-identify-name
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may assume that they need to identify and name specific structural devices in their structural analysis."""@en ;
  curric:correction """An answer simply referencing 'the beginning, middle and end' can make for a successful structural analysis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685073Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-societys-attitudes-towards-female-pleasure
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Society's attitudes towards female pleasure have completely changed since the 1800s."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While society's attitudes towards female pleasure are less extreme than in the 1800s, arguably there is still a sense of shame attached to female pleasure in modern society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685150Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quotation-text-adds-weight-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any quotation from the text adds weight to your argument."@en ;
  curric:correction """For a quotation to be effective, it has to be relevant to the point you are making."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685184Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-poem-poet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the speaker of the poem is the poet."@en ;
  curric:correction """A poet may talk about their own experiences through the speaker, or they may be exploring another aspect of the human psyche and experience through the speaker."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685189Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-effective-comparative-analysis-leads-comparing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Effective comparative analysis leads by comparing the poets' use of literary methods."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The most effective comparative analysis writing should lead by comparing key ideas of attitudes in both poems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685195Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparing-poems-means-focusing-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That comparing poems means focusing on their similarities."@en ;
  curric:correction """The most effective comparisons look for subtle differences within wider similarities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pinnock-doesnt-value-formal-education
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pinnock doesn't value formal education."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pinnock sees the very real power of formal education, but opens our eyes to how that power has been used for ill, and how it could be used for good."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-typically-literature-presents-idea-simple
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Typically, literature presents the idea of a simple life as dull and monotonous."@en ;
  curric:correction """Literary movements such as the Romantics presented an idealised view of a simple, rural existence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685220Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-one-right-interpretation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students often think that there is only 'one right interpretation' of a poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students are shown in this lesson that poetry can be read in several different ways and that any interpretation is valid. Students should be encouraged to explore multiple interpretations when discussing poetry."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685225Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-effective-comparisons-come-poems-obvious
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The most effective comparisons only come from poems with the most obvious similarities."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Insightful comparisons can often emerge from contrasting poems. Exploring differences can uncover complexity and nuance, enriching analysis beyond what similarity alone can achieve."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685229Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-geralds-actions-based-entirely-kindess
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Gerald's actions are based entirely on kindess and he did a good thing in supporting Eva."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Gerald’s actions may seem kind, but they are driven by self-interest and privilege. He offers Eva financial support, but it is not out of pure kindness—he uses his power to control her, ultimately exploiting her for his own benefit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-using-long-quotations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes think that using long quotations offers the best evidence for your point."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Using short, embedded quotations is the most effective way of evidencing your ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685263Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-del-doesnt-value-formal-education
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Del doesn't value formal education."@en ;
  curric:correction """Del does see the value in formal education, but was turned away from it through a lack of support and understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685269Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-women-slaves-patriarchal-societies
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That women were slaves in patriarchal societies."@en ;
  curric:correction """While women had less legal power in patriarchal societies, they could still be very influential and powerful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685274Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-become-reliant-quotation-dagger
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students become over-reliant on the quotation: "Is this a dagger which I see before me?""""@en ;
  curric:correction """Draw attention to other quotations which both illustrate Macbeth can see a dagger, but also demonstrate the flaws in his character."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685278Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-lady-macbeth-holds
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils believe Lady Macbeth holds most of the responsibility for Macbeth's actions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When considering the witches' role, ask pupils which ideas can be used to counter the significance of Lady Macbeth's role in his downfall?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685284Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-know-everything-narrator-their-world
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """We have to know everything about a narrator and their world in order for a story to make sense."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Through slow crafting of a voice, we can let our reader work out the true nature of our narrator, world and characters as they read."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685289Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-play-resolved-offers-clear-conclusion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If a play is not resolved or offers a clear conclusion it is not effective and just feels uncomfortable for the audience."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, this is what the writer wants you to feel with an ambiguous ending. An unresolved ending may provoke more questions and be used by the writer to make a point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-realise-talk-theme-nature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might not realise that they can talk about how the theme of nature is used in a poem, as well as how it is presented."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Keats and Dickinson both use the theme of nature as a vehicle to explore human emotion. Here, the theme of nature is used almost as a method in the poems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685321Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-include-reference-wider-context
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You need to include a reference to the wider context in every analytical paragraph."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The best analytical responses only include relevant pieces of context and weave it subtly throughout. It is important to include context in your answer but it isn't necessary to include it in every paragraph."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685330Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-play-definitely-religious-allegory-interpretations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The play is definitely a religious allegory, and all interpretations align with this view."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While the religious allegory is a valid interpretation, it’s important to consider it as one lens. Focussing on one interpretation may limit a deeper analysis of the text’s complexity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685382Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hyde-solely-presented-dangerous-character
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Hyde is solely presented as a dangerous character from the start to the end of the novella."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Through the character of Hyde, and others' interactions with him, we can explore Stevenson's wider cautionary message."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685387Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-fail-recognise-scrooge-doesnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students fail to recognise that Scrooge doesn't just buy the Cratchits any old turkey."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Scrooge buys the Cratchits the "prize" (or most expensive) turkey. This shows that he is truly generous, as he goes above and beyond."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685393Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-marleys-message-christianity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that Marley's message is only about Christianity and not aimed at everyone."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Marley's Ghost's message is one of morality. When he alludes to biblical parables, he does it to draw attention to their moral lessons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685405Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-attitudes-strong-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that attitudes are often strong and one dimensional."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage them to think about how it is possible for a book or a film to be both frightening and enjoyable."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685409Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-romantic-poems-compared
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that all 'Romantic' poems should be compared, all 'war' poems must be compared, all 'nature' poems must be compared."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The nuances of the question are the most important factor when deciding which poems to compare."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dukes-presentation-himself-absolute-power
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Duke's presentation of himself is of absolute power."@en ;
  curric:correction """If you look deeper into Browning's presentation of the Duke, he is revealed to lack power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-correct-way-organising-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That there is one correct way of organising your thoughts for a plan."@en ;
  curric:correction """Creating a plan is designed to help you see what your argument is - there is no definitive way of how you should organise your thoughts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685445Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sibilance-used-create-sinister-atmosphere
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sibilance is only used to create a sinister atmosphere."@en ;
  curric:correction "The repetition of 's' sound could also create a calming, soothing sound."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685450Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-once-written-response
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that once they have written a response, it is the finished product."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The first draft is simply a first attempt - improvements can always be made and the second draft is always stronger."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685479Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-home-set-bricks-mortar
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That a home is just a set of bricks and mortar."@en ;
  curric:correction """A home offers us a place of refuge and safety - without a home we feel lost and unsure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-write-poem-know-best
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You should always write about the poem you know best."@en ;
  curric:correction """You should write about the two poems that form the best complementary pairing for the question."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685510Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-title-poem-poppies-cause-students
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The title of the poem 'Poppies' may cause the students to immediately link 'Poppies' with another WW1 poem e.g. 'Exposure'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is better to look at comparing poems on the basis of themes and big ideas rather than the time periods in which they were based. 'Poppies' is not a WW1 poem but instead uses the symbol of a poppy in the title to explore grief and loss."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685519Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-leave-taking-either-universal-specific
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """'Leave Taking' is either universal, or about specific experiences and characters."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Like with many texts, we must hold both the idea of Leave Taking's universal themes with the specific experiences of its characters."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685529Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mollie-character-interested-sugar-luxury
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mollie is the only character interested in sugar as a luxury."@en ;
  curric:correction """Napoleon orders sugar for his table and his consumption alone. What does this tell us about the hypocrisy of the pigs?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685574Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-snowball-isnt-deceptive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Snowball isn't deceptive."@en ;
  curric:correction """Does Snowball enjoy the "milk and apples" too? What is he awarded after the Battle of the Cowshed and how does this position Snowball?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685578Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-singhs-wife-presented-exclusively-sweet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Singh's wife is presented exclusively as a sweet and gentle character."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Singh does speak softly of his wife, she also has a fierce streak. This is shown when her eyes are described as like 'guns' and through the description of her arguments with Singh's parents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685587Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-actually-climbing-mountain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The speaker is actually climbing a mountain."@en ;
  curric:correction """The speaker compares the experience of climbing up his Grandfather's body as a child to climbing up a mountain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685601Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-calls-himself-unfinished-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The speaker calls himself "unfinished" because he didn't participate in the initiation ceremony."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The line says that his tribe would consider him unfinished, but doesn't explain how the speaker himself feels."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685612Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-imagery-one-set-meaning-connotations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That imagery has one set meaning and connotations."@en ;
  curric:correction """The connotations of an image can change depending on the language used in relation to it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685617Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ideas-one-essay-question-cant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Ideas for one essay question can't be used in any other essay on the same text."@en ;
  curric:correction """By the end of exploring and writing about a text, you will realise that there are certain ideas and references which you can rely on over and over."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685671Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-know-exact-rhythm-analyse
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you need to know the exact rhythm to analyse it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Determining whether a rhythm is regular or irregular can be a way of analysing the structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685678Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poetic-voice-poem-definitely-imtiaz
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poetic voice in the poem is definitely Imtiaz Dharker."@en ;
  curric:correction """While Dharker uses some of her life experiences as references in the poem (Glasgow, 1960s and 1970s), there are also many examples which may not relate to her life. Arguably she is trying to seem relatable to all readers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685686Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-effective-essay-includes-your-thoughts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "An effective essay includes all of your thoughts on the subject."@en ;
  curric:correction "An effective essay is structured cohesively rather than including every thought."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685693Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparison-answers-focus-differences-poems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Comparison answers should only focus on the differences between poems."@en ;
  curric:correction """Comparisons should focus on both the similarities and differences between the poems to reveal the subtle unique intentions of the poets."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685698Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-isnt-purpose-analytical-writing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That there isn't a purpose to analytical writing."@en ;
  curric:correction """The purpose of analytical writing is to convince the reader of your ideas about the text(s)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685724Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-browning-writing-his-own-wifes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Browning was writing about his own wife's domineering father."@en ;
  curric:correction "Biographical moments in the poet's own life are not always relevant to the poem."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685728Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-order-poem-doesnt-matter
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the order of the poem doesn't matter."@en ;
  curric:correction """The order of the poem impacts when we are exposed to different ideas and emotions which influences the overall tone and meaning of the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685733Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-account-byrons-affair-lady-frances
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "This is an account of Byron's affair with Lady Frances Webster."@en ;
  curric:correction """It is believed that is poem is inspired by Byron's affair with Lady Webster. It is not a factual account, only perhaps a creative interpretation of his feelings about this and other affairs he was known to have had."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685737Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animal-farm-simple-story-leadership
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That 'Animal Farm' is a simple story about leadership and power."@en ;
  curric:correction """Stylistically it is simple, but why does Orwell do this? What does he hope to achieve by making his novella accessible?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685743Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-clear-distinctions-good-leaders-bad
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That there are clear distinctions between good leaders and bad leaders in 'Animal Farm'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although 'Animal Farm' is simply written, its messages are complex. What is Orwell wanting to reveal about leadership in general?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685748Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-byron-based-poem-religious-conflict
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Byron based this poem on a religious conflict which occurred during his lifetime."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem describes a conflict which was described in the Bible, when King Sennacherib and the Assyrian army attempted to attack Jerusalem and were prevented by a divine intervention."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685757Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-want-told-right-answer
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often want to be told the 'right' answer in English and think there is a right answer for every question."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are no 'right' answers in this lesson - this lesson asks students to consider different possibilities and interpretations and to make up their own minds about the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685769Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-sonnet-written-whilst
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might think that this sonnet was written whilst Barrett Browning was married."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem was written before the pair were married. Barrett Browning knew of her father's disapproval, but loved Robert Browning very much."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-ive-written-my-essay
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once I’ve written my essay, I don’t need to think about it again."@en ;
  curric:correction """When you have the opportunity to rewrite or redraft your work, you should take it! It helps you deepen your thinking, develop your ideas more clearly, and express yourself with greater precision. Writing is a process, not just a product."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-birlings-guilty-crimes-inspector-calls
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Birlings are not guilty of any crimes in 'An Inspector Calls' because they do not face legal consequences."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While the Birlings do not face legal prosecution, Priestley uses their moral failings to argue that crime is not only a legal matter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685887Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stevenson-presents-good-evil-complete
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Stevenson presents good and evil as complete opposites."@en ;
  curric:correction "Remind students how easily Hyde and Jekyll blur into one."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685892Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-lees-account-true
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may think that Lee's account is true of all North Koreans."@en ;
  curric:correction """Draw attention to the fact the book is a memoir. It is personal and about what she recalls and what she felt. The context helps us appreciate her own experience."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685896Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-longer-experience-gender-inequality-todays
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "We no longer experience gender inequality in today's society."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although today's society is much more progressive than Victorian society, there are still areas where gender inequality is experienced, although it is usually much more subtle and institutionalised."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685903Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-accepted-interpretation-poem
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That there is one accepted interpretation of a poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """People may interpret and respond to poetry differently because poetry is, at its core, about emotion and we all have different emotion responses to stimuli."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poet-part-one-literary-movement
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That a poet can only be a part of one literary movement."@en ;
  curric:correction """Often, we can see poets as referencing more than one literary movement and that can help us understand the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-banquos-main-purpose-play-act
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Banquo's main purpose in the play is to act as a foil, highlighting Macbeth's treachery."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore the purpose of Fleance, by asking pupils how they think events would have unfolded if Fleance had been killed too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685916Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-contextual-information-essay-comprise-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Contextual information in an essay should comprise of one final sentence in each paragraph."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Context should be weaved throughout an essay to help explore a writer's intentions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inspector-ghost-his-supernatural-qualitites
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Inspector is a ghost and his supernatural qualitites should be interpreted literally."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst this is one interpretation, it must be considered alongside the symbolic value of the Inspector’s supernatural elements and Priestley’s purpose."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-stevensons-ambiguity-hydes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might think Stevenson's ambiguity about Hyde's appearance is due to insufficient detail."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stevenson keeps Hyde's description vague to engage readers' imaginations, amplifying the character's eeriness."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685932Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-spotting-lots-different-features-makes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That spotting lots of different features makes a good analysis."@en ;
  curric:correction """Simply spotting a feature is too superficial. The best analysis will say a lot about little. Being able to develop multiple comments on a single feature, creates a much better more in-depth analysis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685937Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-need-write-exciting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that they need to write an 'exciting' story which includes lots of action."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A genuinely engaging story allows the reader to empathise with the character(s) and experience the same emotions as them, at the same time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685944Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-exam-questions-need
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils believe that all exam questions need unique ideas and responses."@en ;
  curric:correction """When looking at the question in the first learning cycle, ask pupils if they can use ideas/arguments from previous 'Macbeth' essays."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685969Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-final-sentence-analytical-paragraph
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Context should be the final sentence of each analytical paragraph."@en ;
  curric:correction """Context should be woven in to paragraphs where relevant; context should help develop and enrich your ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mentioning-stevensons-choices-surrounding-form
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Just mentioning Stevenson's choices surrounding form and structure is valuable analysis."""@en ;
  curric:correction """All comments regarding Stevenson's use of form and structure should be tied back to Stevenson's purpose."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685977Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-belle-interested-money
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students believe that Belle was never interested in having any money."@en ;
  curric:correction """Belle was interested in having money - she just wanted to earn it with Scrooge over time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685984Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-need-analyse-writers-attitude
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """We don't need to analyse the writer's attitude in non-fiction because it's all factual information."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Analysing the writer's attitude in non-fiction is important because it helps us to understand why the writer has presented information in a certain way and how they want us to interpret the information."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inference-analysis-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Inference and analysis are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Inference is about reading between the lines. Analysis focuses on unpicking writer's methods and explores their effects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685993Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysing-poems-structure-boring-intimidating
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That analysing a poem's structure is boring and intimidating."@en ;
  curric:correction """One way of looking at structure might be to imagine it as a heartbeat - why does the poem 'beat' regularly or irregularly? What emotion might that signify?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.685997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shelley-romantic-poet-meant-his
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Shelley was a Romantic poet which meant all of his poems were love poems."@en ;
  curric:correction """Romantic poetry did sometimes focus on themes associated with love, but not exclusively. Romantic poetry is instead characterised by its dramatic approach to exploring abstract and emotional concepts such as a love, nature or the supernatural."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-west-egg-east
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might believe that West Egg and East Egg are actual geographical locations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While West Egg and East Egg are based on real places on Long Island, they are fictional locations created by Fitzgerald to symbolise different social classes and the contrasts between new and old wealth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686006Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-realise-choose-unique-narrative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not realise that they can choose a unique narrative perspective for their creative writing as they may not have come across that many narrative perspectives other than human."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Tell pupils that writers have written from the perspective of animals, objects, abstract ideas etc. Give examples. 'Black Beauty' is written from a horse's perspective. 'The Book Thief' is narrated by Death."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686012Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-traditional-story-arc-applied-full
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The traditional story arc can only be applied to full narratives."@en ;
  curric:correction "You can find elements of the traditional story arc in writing of any length."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-select-quotations-spotting-methods-within
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you should select quotations by spotting methods within a poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """While analysing methods is an important part of understanding a text, selecting quotations should focus on which word(s) create an evocative impression."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686024Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-used-encountering-detached-third
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may be used to encountering a detached third person narrator thus expecting most narrators to be trustworthy and reliable."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When a writer chooses to write a story from a characters' perspective, we have to consider that each character  is fallible or unreliable. Thus, we have to re-filter (through our own consciousness) the information we get from a first person narrator."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686028Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-leave-taking-commentary-experiences-women
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Leave Taking' is a commentary on the experiences of all women."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pinnock presents the unique stories of her created characters. The centrality of women suggests she is making some sort of social comment, but she is not generalising about every single woman's experience of the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rhetorical-question-answered-designed-make
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A rhetorical question is never answered. It is designed to make people think."@en ;
  curric:correction """While a rhetorical question is designed to encourage the reader or audience to consider their views on the subject matter, a writer can choose to answer the rhetorical question conveying their opinions (but they don't have to)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686037Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-tell-story-chronologically
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students often think that they have to tell a story chronologically."@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage them to consider how many books and films start with an exciting event and then go back to explain the exposition of the story."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-schoolboys-simple-language-regular-structure
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """'The Schoolboy’s' simple language and regular structure suggest that it is a straightforward poem about childhood rather than a deeper critique of institutional control."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While the language and structure may seem simple, Blake uses them deliberately to reflect the monotony and rigidity of school life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686048Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-male-characters-shakespeares-romeo-juliet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the male characters in Shakespeare's 'Romeo and Juliet' are always keen to fight."""@en ;
  curric:correction "In Act 5, Scene 3, Romeo and Paris both seem reluctant to fight."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686107Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-identifying-method-quotation-effective
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That just identifying a method in a quotation is effective."@en ;
  curric:correction "To be effective, you need to analyse the effect of the method in the quotation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686111Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-reason-macbeth-doesnt-want
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There is just one reason that Macbeth doesn't want to commit regicide - his loyalty to Duncan."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Macbeth's soliloquy explores crime but significantly earthly punishment. For Macbeth, the consequence on earth is what frightens him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686116Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-tentative-language-makes-sound
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Using tentative language makes you sound unsure in your analysis."@en ;
  curric:correction """Tentative language allows pupils to be more evaluative, exploring alternative viewpoints."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686121Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-sassoons-style-open
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that Sassoon's style of open letter is the only way to write an open letter."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Open letters can have a range of purposes. Those that will never be read by the recipient or where the writer doesn't expect to create change (e.g. open letter to Mondays) will typically involve more humour."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686125Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-descriptions-colours-provide-visual-aid
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That descriptions of colours are only there to provide a visual aid."@en ;
  curric:correction "Colour symbolism is deeply important to the meaning of the poem as well."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686136Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-important-part-writing-dialogue-thinking
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the only important part of writing a dialogue is thinking about which words the characters are going to use."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When writing dialogue, you want to consider how you can show emotion through descriptions of facial expressions, body language, and your use of punctuation and structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686143Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-case-now-hyde-found-dead
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The case is over now Hyde has been found dead."@en ;
  curric:correction """Get students enthused about the final mystery - how has Jekyll disappeared from a room locked from the inside?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686152Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-alliteration-onomatopoeia-devices-used-fiction
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Alliteration and onomatopoeia are devices used only in fiction writing (e.g. stories)."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Alliteration and onomatopoeia are both types of aural device because they link to how writers use sounds. This means they are particularly useful for speeches because they are delivered aloud (as opposed to read)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686156Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-feels-though-doesnt-belong
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The speaker feels as though he doesn't belong in either 'home' (Zambia or the UK)."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The speaker seems to identify more with his African culture, reflecting on how his identity is "unfinished" which implies it isn't lost completely."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686165Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-zephaniahs-description-his-mother-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Zephaniah's description of his "mother country" shows that his Jamaican cultural identity is more important to him that his British identity."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Prior to Jamaican independence in 1962, many Jamaicans referred to the UK as their "mother country". This suggests that Zephaniah's British identity is very important to him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686170Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-casey-working-class-wrote-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Casey was working class and wrote about her own life experiences in the poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """Not much is known about Mary Casey. She did come from a working class background but we cannot be certain if this poem reflects her own life experiences. This is why it is important to use tentative language when analysing a literary text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686175Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-used-paragraph-comparative-analytical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Context should be used in every paragraph of a comparative analytical response."@en ;
  curric:correction """While it is extremely important to use relevant contextual information to shape interpretations of the two poems being compared, it isn't necessary to include it in every paragraph unless it is relevant to the overall argument you are making."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686181Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-idea-life-temporary-sad-notion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the idea of life being temporary must always be a sad notion."@en ;
  curric:correction "The idea of life being temporary might inspire us to live life to the fullest."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686186Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rhythm-characters-speech-unimportant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the rhythm of a character's speech is unimportant."@en ;
  curric:correction "Exploring the rhythm of a character's speech can reveal their emotional state."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686191Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-argument-lady-macbeth-involves-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The only argument about Lady Macbeth involves her being subversive."@en ;
  curric:correction """Characters can be interpreted in different ways. Your role is to construct a strong argument, not the 'right' argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686195Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-including-statistics-enough-make-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Including any statistics is enough to make your argument more convincing."@en ;
  curric:correction "In order to be convincing, statistics have to be credible."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-adding-alternative-interpretation-weakens-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Adding an alternative interpretation weakens your argument."@en ;
  curric:correction """Showing how you can reach the same conclusion about a text through multiple interpretations strengthens your argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-need-describe-everything
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that they need to describe everything in a setting."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask students to 'bounce' around a scene, only describing the most influential and important aspects of it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-punctuation-used-ensure-writing-makes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Punctuation is only used to ensure writing makes sense."@en ;
  curric:correction """Punctuation can be a stylistic choice from a writer, contributing to the tension of a story."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686260Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-men-supposed-bigger-man-act
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That men were supposed to be the 'bigger man' and act rationally in the face of a challenge to their honour."""@en ;
  curric:correction "In Elizabethan England, men were expected to defend their honour."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686265Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thesis-topic-sentences-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Thesis and topic sentences are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction "A thesis must be overarching. A topic sentence can be much more specific."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686278Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-witches-presented-one-way-new
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The witches are presented in one way; any new interpretation supersedes the one before."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The witches are presented as supernatural, women, masculine and genderless. Paragraphs can explore all these; rely on LC2 to draw this out."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686283Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-our-personal-response-poem-isnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That our personal response to a poem isn't a valid form of analysis."@en ;
  curric:correction """Poems are outpourings of emotion and therefore our personal response is incredibly important as it allows us to work towards understanding the emotion behind the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686292Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dialogue-superfluous-part-text-cant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That dialogue is a superfluous part of a text and can't be analysed in the same way as other structural or language features."""@en ;
  curric:correction """We can analyse dialogue by considering how it's structured, how the conversation is divided up, the use of punctuation and through the use of body language."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686298Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-recognise-terms-endearment-patronising
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may not recognise how terms of endearment can be patronising."@en ;
  curric:correction """Terms of endearment are traditionally used as a sign of affection but they can be used to subdue, belittle or appease someone (depending on the context)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686302Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-entitled-their-own-opinion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """'Everyone is entitled to their own opinion', therefore there is no need to justify our opinions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although we are all entitled to our opinion, justifying your opinion allows people to trust and listen to your opinion more carefully."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686307Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-sophisticated-vocabulary-alone-enough
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Using sophisticated vocabulary alone is enough to make my writing great."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although sophisticated vocabulary is good, there are lots of smaller strategies that can also make writing effective."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686312Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-get-mixed-noun-appositive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often get mixed up between a noun appositive and a relative clause."@en ;
  curric:correction """The relative pronoun 'who' could lead to pupils trying to add too much extra detail about a character, a noun appositive encourages brevity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686318Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-characters-referred-real-people-example
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The characters are referred to as real people. For example "Old Major describes himself as ...""""@en ;
  curric:correction """Think about the purpose of the characters and why Orwell has constructed them the way he has."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686323Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-need-analyse-non-fiction
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you don't need to analyse non-fiction texts - just absorb the information."@en ;
  curric:correction """Analysing non-fiction texts is essential because it helps us understand who is offering us this information and why are they offering it to us."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686328Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-need-exciting-experiences
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that they need exciting experiences to write in a compelling manner."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Stress how the quality of writing is more important than the topic being written about."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686365Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-personal-responses-involve-making-guesses
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That personal responses involve making guesses about the writer's context and state of mind."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Personal responses consider how and why a poem might create a certain emotion in the reader or what they say about society in general."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686375Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-consider-image-simile-offers-us
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That we should only consider the image that a simile offers us."@en ;
  curric:correction """While the image may be particularly evocative, it's also useful to analyse the connotations of the comparative image as that can reveal layers to what the writer is trying to portray to the reader."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686380Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-macbeth-jacobean
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Macbeth is a Jacobean."@en ;
  curric:correction """'Macbeth' is set in 11th century Scotland. However, it was first performed in 1606 in front of a Jacobean audience."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686386Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-viv-del-enid-british-citizens
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Viv, Del and Enid are not British citizens."@en ;
  curric:correction """All three women are British citizens. Enid relocated from one part of the Commonwealth to another. During this post war period, this ensured legal status in Britain. Viv and Del were born in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686391Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-discourse-around-teenagers-1950s-60s
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Discourse around teenagers in the 1950s and 60s would be entirely different to discourse around teenagers nowadays."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There are some strong similarities between the media portrayal of teenagers from decades ago and now e.g. their ability to shape trends."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686396Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-tone-mood-poem-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the tone and mood of the poem are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Tone refers to the attitude of the writer towards the subject matter while mood refers to the effect the writing has on the reader."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analyse-techniques-poet-chooses-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you can only analyse what techniques a poet chooses to use."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sometimes it's very powerful to analyse why a poet may have chosen not to use a technique in contrast to one who did choose to use it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686404Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-isnt-fact-mr-birling-wants
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Isn't the fact that Mr. Birling wants to look after himself and his family a good thing?"""@en ;
  curric:correction """It's understandable to think that Mr. Birling's focus on looking after himself and his family could be seen as positive.  However, Priestley shows that Mr. Birling's attitude is self-serving and dismissive of wider societal responsibilities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-accustomed-forming-opinion-narrator
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may not be accustomed to forming an opinion on a narrator, typically seeing them as a neutral figure in a story."""@en ;
  curric:correction """First person narrators are often protagonists of their stories and they can retell the events in any way they want to. This allows us to be critical of a narrator."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686437Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-develop-personal-response-asking-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That we can develop a personal response by asking the same questions of every non-fiction text."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While some questions are universal, a non-fiction text such as a personal essay may require us to ask questions about what the writer want us to understand about their lives in order for us to respond to it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686444Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-required-paragraph-comparative-analytical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Context is required in every paragraph of a comparative analytical response."@en ;
  curric:correction """Context is important to include in your response but it isn't necessary in every paragraph. In order to avoid 'bolt-on' context, it should only be used when it is relevant to the point you're making in that paragraph."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686452Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-consider-bigger-picture-text-rather
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you should consider the bigger picture of a text rather than minute detail."@en ;
  curric:correction """Zooming in on individual words is a powerful analytical tool that allows you to see patterns in meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686457Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-using-figurative-language
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think using figurative language to describe emotions means using similes and metaphors."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Students should use figurative language more subtly, in verbs and adjectives to create extended metaphors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686461Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-slang-colloquialisms-idioms-narrative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can never use slang, colloquialisms and idioms in narrative writing."@en ;
  curric:correction """If slang, colloquialism and idioms are part of your narrative voice, it is okay to use them but you have to ensure your use of them comes across as deliberate, consistent and that you have secure grammar and control over the piece of work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686466Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-planning-paragraph-describe-different-aspect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Planning each paragraph to describe a different aspect of the scene will always create an engaging description."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Describing something different in each paragraph does not necessarily lead to an interesting description - it is the way in which the paragraphs link and build curiosity and tension that can make it more engaging."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686470Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-main-subordinate-clauses-merely-grammatical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Main and subordinate clauses are merely grammatical terms not worthy of analysis."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A writer's decision to use subordinate and main clauses is a creative choice. Their use can achieve different things (e.g. tension, pace)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686475Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-juliet-romeos-love-shakespeares-romeo
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Juliet was Romeo's only love in Shakespeare's 'Romeo and Juliet'."@en ;
  curric:correction "Before Juliet, Romeo believes himself to be in love with Rosaline."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686479Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-first-scene-exciting-spectacle-important
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The first scene is an exciting spectacle but not important to the rest of the play."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Despite its length, this scene grounds us in the atmosphere and main themes of the play."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686484Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-accustomed-writing-informative-articles
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may be more accustomed to writing informative articles. In Learning Cycle 2, they may want to explain how love has changed over time rather than give their opinion on it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Students can create a more engaging article, which is more vibrant with a clear sense of voice, by including their opinion on a topic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686490Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-text-sole-purpose
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students sometimes think that a text has a sole purpose e.g. only to persuade or only to argue."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Draw their attention to the tone of Mark Twain's speech - he's quite humorous."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686495Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-present-balanced-view
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often think that they should present a balanced view in opinion-based writing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is much more convincing and persuasive to only present one side of the argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-malcolm-immoral-person
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Malcolm is an immoral person."@en ;
  curric:correction """Malcolm pretends he is filled with lust and greed, but this is to test Macduff's loyalty."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686535Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysing-play-focus-characters-dialogue
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "When analysing a play, you only focus on the characters' dialogue."@en ;
  curric:correction """Stage directions can provide a lot of clues around the writer's intention and vision. They also offer an understanding of charcaterisation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686539Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thesis-statements-topic-sentences-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That thesis statements and topic sentences are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Differentiate; the thesis statement is a comment on the text as a whole, and a topic sentence has a focus on a specific part of the text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686548Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-belfast-confetti-metaphor-created-carson
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "'Belfast Confetti' is a metaphor created by Carson in this poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """The term 'Belfast Confetti' was used during The Troubles to refer to the homemade bombs used in the fighting. They were called this because they were filled with shrapnel which, when detonated, sprayed in the sky like confetti."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686558Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-blake-romantic-poet-artist-thus
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Blake was a Romantic poet and artist and thus was critical of many societal beliefs and attitudes, namely religion which was called into question in the Enlightenment period just prior to this."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Romantics did acknowledge and agree with many Enlightenment ideas but, by and large, they were religious in their writing. Blake was a deeply religious man and his critique of religion was focused mainly on how it was interpreted by society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686564Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-clear-deifnite-interpretation-charcater
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is always one clear and deifnite interpretation of a charcater."@en ;
  curric:correction """Characters can have multiple interpretations based on context, perspective, and evidence in the text. Writers like Priestley create complex characters to provoke debate and reflection."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686569Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thesis-statement-rewording-essay-question
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A thesis statement is just a rewording of the essay question."@en ;
  curric:correction """The essay question is useful in formulating a thesis, however try using key question vocabulary and using it to form your own argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lady-macbeths-unsex-me-means
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lady Macbeth's 'unsex me' here means she wants to be a man."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst she might want some masculine qualities, there are more implications to this. She could be calling for supernatural qualities too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686634Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-christians-against-scientific-development
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Christians were against scientific development."@en ;
  curric:correction """Within all religions (or groups in society) there will be plurality of thought, including progressive viewpoints."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686640Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-consider-imagery-literal-face-value
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That we should consider imagery at literal, face value."@en ;
  curric:correction """While considering the literal meaning is good for our understanding, we want to move beyond that to consider what a quotation or image symbolises and what it is saying about the wider ideas in the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686646Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-fail-realise-dont-write
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often fail to realise that they don't have to write from their own perspective."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Inform pupils that it can be incredibly powerful to write from another, imagined perspective."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analyse-one-poem-analyse-second
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You should analyse one poem and then analyse the second, making your comparisons at this point."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The best analysis writing weaves comparisons throughout. A great way to practise this is by beginning each paragraph with a topic sentence that uses correlative conjunctions (e.g. both ... and ...)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparative-response-focus-differences-two
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A comparative response should only focus on the differences between two poems."@en ;
  curric:correction """An effective comparative response considers the similarities between the poems as well as nuanced differences within those similarities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686661Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poppies-poem-mother-whose-son
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Poppies is a poem about a mother whose son died during WWI."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Poppies are a symbol of remembrance for those who died in WWI, Weir uses her poem to draw attention to the many conflicts that have occurred throughout history. It isn't clear which conflict the son is heading off to fight in."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686710Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-man-killed-exposure-war-photographer
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """'The Man He Killed', 'Exposure', 'War Photographer' and 'What Were They Like?' display a purely negative and critical attitude to war."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Thomas Hardy's 'The Man He Killed' certainly questions the dehumanising nature of war but arguably isn't quite as critical as other war poems since in the last stanza the speaker describes war and killing enemy soldiers as "quaint" and "curious"."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-valid-interpretation-method
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is only one valid interpretation of a method."@en ;
  curric:correction "There might be several different ways of interpreting a method."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686730Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-writing-c18th-use-romantic-conventions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You have to be writing in the C18th to use Romantic conventions in your writing."@en ;
  curric:correction """While Romanticism was a predominant movement in the C18th and C19th, more modern poets can also adhere to Romantic conventions and present a Romantic view of the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686734Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-need-bother-conclusion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "I don't need to bother with a conclusion."@en ;
  curric:correction """Who will be reading your response? Imagine them reading your final sentence, how do you want them to feel?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686779Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enjambment-simply-creates-flow-poem
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That enjambment simply creates flow in a poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """Enjambment usually links to the conceptual continuation of an idea of theme within the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-way-interpret-regular-rhyme-scheme
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The only way to interpret a regular rhyme scheme is to suggest that it brings a sense of calmness to the poem."""@en ;
  curric:correction """As well as a sense of calm, a regular rhyme scheme can also create ideas of control and predictability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686788Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-evoking-ideas-deities-means-something
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Evoking ideas of deities always means that something is positive and divine."@en ;
  curric:correction """While evoking deities can confer notions of divinity, we also need to consider the story behind the deity and how that story can add meaning to the narrative."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686829Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-poem-wordsworths-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that this poem is just about Wordsworth's time ice-skating as a child."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The poem also portrays the sheer power and beauty of nature. It is as much about nature as it is Wordsworth's childhood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-since-normally-compare-two-poems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Since you normally only compare two poems, it's not useful to make connections across the whole anthology."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Making connections across the whole anthology allows you to see the threads that connect the poems which will extend your comparative responses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-parent-child-spoke
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some pupils may think the parent and child never spoke or saw each other again after this moment in the poem."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The separation described in the poem isn't just physical but rather emotional. Day-Lewis describes a moment where the speaker feels like they lost a part of their son because he had grown up and gained his independence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-learn-lots-quotes-write
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You need to learn lots of quotes to write a successful essay."@en ;
  curric:correction """Picking a few 'hard working', analytically rich quotes is a better strategy. It's what you do with them that counts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poems-anthology-focus-particular-war
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All of the poems in this anthology focus on a particular war from history."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are some war poems in the anthology which focus on particular conflicts (e.g. 'Destruction of Sennacherib' and 'Charge of the Light Brigade') but others which focus more on societal conflicts (e.g. racism, social class)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-troubles-war-occurred-armies-uk
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Troubles was a war that occurred between the armies of the UK and the Republic of Ireland."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Troubles were fought in Northern Ireland between the unionists (who wanted NI to remain in the UK) and the nationalists (who wanted NI to join the ROI). Most of the fighting occurred between paramilitary groups."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686938Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-doesnt-seem-like-typical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """This poem doesn’t seem like a typical love poem because it doesn’t present love as happy or ideal. Most love poetry tends to focus on idealised romantic love."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ewing shows love as fragile but meaningful. By exploring romantic, familial, and self-love, she challenges idealised love poetry and redefines what love can look like—real, complex, and powerful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686947Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-childhood-memories-summer-picking
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poem is just about the childhood memories of summer and picking fruit."@en ;
  curric:correction """Heaney uses the extended metaphor of blackberry picking to explore nostalgia and the fleeting nature of youth and time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686951Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-boxer-presented-na-ve-gullible
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Boxer is only presented as naïve and gullible."@en ;
  curric:correction """Why does Napoleon set the dogs on Boxer? There are moments when Boxer begins to challenge what he is being told by the pigs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686967Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-temper-means-anger
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That 'temper' means anger."@en ;
  curric:correction """While we might associate 'temper' with a 'temper tantrum', 'temper' can refer to any emotional frame of mind."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-journey-physical-undertaking
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That a journey is always a physical undertaking."@en ;
  curric:correction """While many journeys are physical undertakings, you can also take a personal or spiritual journey towards improvement and growth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-written-soldiers-fighting-wwi
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "This poem is written about soldiers fighting in WWI."@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem was published during the Second Boer War (1899-1902) fought during the Victorian era. The First World War wouldn't begin for another 12 years."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687045Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dreams-arent-based-reality
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That dreams aren't based on reality."@en ;
  curric:correction "Dreams often draw on our previous memories or experiences."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687050Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-final-word-poem-unimportant-detail
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The final word of a poem is an unimportant detail."@en ;
  curric:correction """The final word of the poem offers us the lasting impression of the poem's message."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687054Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-social-responsibility-means-helping-need
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Social responsibility means just helping those in need."@en ;
  curric:correction """Social responsibility is about considering the impact of our actions on others and society, not just charity. It involves accountability for our role in social issues, like inequality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687101Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-included-paragraph
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Context must be included in every paragraph."@en ;
  curric:correction """Context must be included in essays, but where it is relevant and develops your analysis - not as a tick box exercise for each paragraph."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-takes-retrospective-view-vietnam
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """This poem takes a retrospective view on the Vietnam War, looking back on the devastation many years later."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The poem is set in an alternate future, set after the Vietnam War had ended (and the US had won). It was actually first published in 1968, while the conflict was still ongoing. The war didn't end until 1975."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687173Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ignore-parts-poem-dont-fit
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You should ignore any parts of the poem that don't fit with your overall interpretation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """To create a nuanced argument, you want to think about why the poet may have chosen not to present a cohesive whole to the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687178Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-recognise-act-storytelling-poem
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may not recognise the act of storytelling in the poem nor the four generations that feature."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to the students the poem has one narrator but she is telling the story in 3rd person at the beginning, later revealing herself as the main character as the poem uses italics."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-first-read-poem-entirely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might first read the poem as entirely literal. e.g. "black'ning church" refers to pollution of the industrial revolution."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Several ideas are metaphorical or symbolic in the poem. E.g. Blake refers to the corruption of the church (the church is also symbolic of religion as a whole)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-planning-effective-use-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That planning is not an effective use of time."@en ;
  curric:correction "Planning helps to to write a developed, detailed and cohesive response."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-immediately-want-compare-tissue
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may immediately want to compare 'Tissue' with ‘The Émigrée’ due to the immediate connection with light and displacement."""@en ;
  curric:correction """If we look more closely at 'Tissue', we can find solid links between poems about the ephemerality of human power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687309Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-structure-poem-entirely-predictable
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The structure of the poem is entirely predictable."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that Blake does break his rigid structure e.g. iambic tetrameter at times."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687313Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-topic-sentences-compare-language-techniques
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Topic sentences should compare language techniques, form and structure."@en ;
  curric:correction """Topic sentences should focus on big ideas as it allows for meaningful comparison."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687318Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-singular-tone-emotion-within
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is one singular tone or emotion within a poem."@en ;
  curric:correction "Often poems express complex and multiple emotions at one time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687329Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-contextual-information-same-relevance-value
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That contextual information all has the same relevance and value."@en ;
  curric:correction """When considering contextual information, you want to consider which information is the most relevant to helping us understand the meaning of the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687333Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-three-poems-explore-conflict-belonging
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All three poems explore conflict and belonging related to cultural identity because all three poets have an intercultural identity."""@en ;
  curric:correction """All three poets have an intercultural identity and this is reflected in many of their poems. However here, only 'Kumukanda' explores these ideas directly. Dharker focuses on identity and growing up; Kunial explores belonging in a more abstract way."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687349Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-spending-much-time-reading-question
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Spending too much time reading the question wastes time when you could be writing the essay."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Spending time reading the question allows us to select what is relevant. It is just as important to know what not to include in a well argued response."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687376Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-porphyria-entirely-passive-without-agency
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Porphyria is entirely passive and without agency."@en ;
  curric:correction """Porphyria displays agency by actively seeking out the speaker and initiating intimacy. Her actions challenge societal norms, reflecting her independence and desire, despite her eventual victimisation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689230Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-change-rhyming-pattern-unimportant-meaning
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A change in the rhyming pattern is unimportant to the meaning of the poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """A change in the rhyme could signify a change in emotion or a conflict/resolution has occurred."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689234Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-texts-compared-others-same-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Texts can only be compared to others from the same time period or literary movement."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, comparing texts across different periods or movements can enrich understanding, as themes, ideas, and literary techniques often transcend time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689268Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-windmill-presented-negative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The windmill is only presented as a negative."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore Snowball's initial plans. How does he view the role of the windmill? Orwell is showing how industry and progress can be exploited."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.689896Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-isnt-much-point-analysing-setting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There isn't much point analysing setting to learn about theh characters or themes of text; it just provides the scenery for the action to take place in."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Often writers use setting to subtly foreshadow events or symbolise important paralells to characters. Analysing settings is a useful way to learn more about characters and key themes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690117Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-epic-form-show-wordsworths
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The use of the epic form is just to show Wordsworth's adventure."@en ;
  curric:correction """The use of epic form may suggest how nature is a heroic or legendary presence worthy of the epic poem form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690446Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-your-imagination-create-imaginary
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That using your imagination to create imaginary games is a way of withdrawing from the world."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While imaginary games can be used to withdraw from the world, our imaginations come from things we have seen or experienced and therefore imaginary games can be a way of connecting to the world and finding your place in it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690491Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cant-explore-dramatic-function-stage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can't explore the dramatic function of off stage characters."@en ;
  curric:correction """Off stage characters can help develop a world beyond the stage itself, grounding the play in its own reality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691112Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-dying-soldier-already
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that the dying soldier was already dead when he was thrown into the wagon."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is important that students understand that the soldier was still half-alive when he was tossed, dying, into the body wagon. This needs to be understood for students to grasp the brutality of war and the lack of respect soldiers were shown."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691191Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poems-present-relationships-dysfunctional-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All of these poems present relationships which are dysfunctional in some way."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although 'Porphyria's Lover' and 'The Farmer's Bride' appear to show abusive, controlling relationships, the relationship in 'Singh Song!' is presented as a much more conventionally loving one."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romantic-poets-purely-concerned-nature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Romantic poets were purely concerned with nature."@en ;
  curric:correction """While nature is a prominent theme of many Romantic poems, Romantics were also social revolutionaries who criticised institutions such as the monarchy and the Church."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-your-first-reading-poem-involve
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That your first reading of a poem should involve finding the techniques used."@en ;
  curric:correction """Reading the poem aloud and then considering the key images within the poem is a more effective way to consider the ideas in the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692620Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mother-feels-loss-her-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The mother feels a loss of her her beauty, confidence and independence after having a child."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It's important to remember that the 'voice' we hear this from is the speaker's (the daughter). In this way, the negative connotations associated with motherhood could be interpreted as the speaker's guilt for taking her mother's freedom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693169Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-notice-significance-textile-imagery
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may not notice the significance of the textile imagery."@en ;
  curric:correction """The textile imagery was carefully chosen for the poem, Jane Weir would have been very conscious of putting this in as she was a textile designer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693306Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysing-punctuation-isnt-effective-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That analysing punctuation isn't an effective way to approaching a poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """Punctuation can affect a reader's journey through the poem as well as their emotional response."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693311Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-brod-contrasts-enid-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Brod contrasts Enid in every way."@en ;
  curric:correction """Brod and Enid clash over education, Jamaica and England, but they also have many commonalities: their past and their migration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693648Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-analyse-poems-title
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students do not think that they can analyse the poem's title."@en ;
  curric:correction """In analytical responses, students can absolutely analyse the poem's title!  This can be a great way to start a response or comparison."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694088Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thesis-statement-summary-poems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The thesis statement is just a summary of the poems."@en ;
  curric:correction """An effective comparative thesis will highlight a key comparison and difference between the texts, showing how they deepen an understanding of the key themes and ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694166Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-effectively-practise-my-presentation-my
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "I can effectively practise my presentation in my head."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although it is good to think about your presentation, you will need to practise delivering it out loud. This will give you a much better idea of timing and pace."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694394Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-victorians-religious-people-meant-behaved
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Most Victorians were religious people which meant that they behaved in a way that was morally good."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While most Victorians were religious and followed stict moral codes, they did so only in public. Behind clsosed doors, immoral and debaucherous behaviour was common."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-immoral-behaviour-something-lower-classes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Immoral behaviour was something only the lower classes engaged in."@en ;
  curric:correction """Immoral behaviour was something that crossed class boundaries but it manifested differently; for the lower classes, vice was survival-based with many turning to crime to survive whereas the wealthy engaged in debauchery and illicit affairs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-stopped-revolution
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the animals could not have stopped the revolution."@en ;
  curric:correction """How does Orwell describe Boxer? He is physically powerful and commands respect. If he had intelligence could he have made a difference?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694456Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-benjamin-minor-character-animal-farm
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Benjamin is a minor character in 'Animal Farm' and doesn't represent much."@en ;
  curric:correction """Could Benjamin make a difference? Could he have used his intelligence? Benjamin's apathy has a key role in the pigs' reign."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694468Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-industrial-revolution-wholly-positive-change
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Industrial Revolution was a wholly positive change for society because machines created jobs and allowed for foriegn travel."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While there were many advantages to the Industrial Revolution, there were also many disadvantages such as pollution, worsening of working conditions and a widening of the class divide."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-introductions-conclusion-arent-important
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Introductions and conclusion aren't important."@en ;
  curric:correction """An effective introduction and conclusion means that a written response is more likely to be well considered and cohesive throughout."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694610Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-orwell-offers-solution-problems-highlights
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Orwell offers a solution to the problems he highlights."@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus on the cyclical structure and lack of resolution. How does this reflect Orwell's purpose? Is he just being critical and cynical?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-old-major-invents-animalism
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Old Major invents Animalism."@en ;
  curric:correction """The three pigs invent Animalism in response to Old Major's speech. What might Orwell be commenting on here or trying to reveal?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694621Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-referencing-contextual-information-poets-useful
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That referencing any contextual information about the poets is useful."@en ;
  curric:correction """Contextual information needs to enhance your argument and understanding of the poem for it to be meaningful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-romantic-poems-love
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students might think Romantic poems are only about love and beauty."@en ;
  curric:correction """Romantic poems also explore deep emotions, the sublime in nature, individualism and sometimes darker themes like sorrow and longing, reflecting the complexity of human experience."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparative-response-needs-reference-two
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A comparative response just needs to reference two poems."@en ;
  curric:correction """A comparative response must explicitly compare two poems on big ideas. It is important to use discourse markers to signpost comparisons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695652Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mais-desire-people-invest-themselves
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mai's desire that people "invest" in themselves is just a way for her to make more money."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst Mai is determined to be paid for her services, she takes her calling seriously."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poverty-enid-faced-jamaica-equivalent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The poverty Enid faced in Jamaica is equivalent to the poverty she faces in England."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Enid faced rural poverty where she "lived off the land". Farming is unreliable, and her family could feasibly become destitute."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695756Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-third-person-limited
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might think that "third person limited" means the narrative is limited in scope or detail."""@en ;
  curric:correction """"Third person limited" means insight into one character's thoughts, not a story's limited scope."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-need-plan-topic-sentences
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You don't need to plan topic sentences in full."@en ;
  curric:correction """Write topic sentences in full when planning. They give the essay structure and make sure you develop and support your thesis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695881Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romantic-poems-beauty-nature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Romantic poems are about the beauty of nature."@en ;
  curric:correction """While Romantic poets often wrote admiringly about nature, they are primarily concerned with their interaction with nature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696064Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-fail-notice-appreciate-defiant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils often fail to notice or appreciate how defiant this poem is at the end."@en ;
  curric:correction """In saying that she will love her future husband "better" after death, Barrett Browning defies her father and any cosmic force which may try to prevent the couple from being together. Barrett Browning's passion and commitment to Browning is evident."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696085Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enids-husband-loved-her-terrible
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Enid's husband never loved her. They had a terrible relationship."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst there are descriptions of conflict in their relationship, the description of their moving to England shows their initial devotion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696808Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-power-sees-education-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That everyone in power sees education as a way to better society."@en ;
  curric:correction """How does it feel when you don't understand something? Confusing? Scary? Disorientating? How could the pigs use this to their advantage?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mais-son-emigrated-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mai's son emigrated with her."@en ;
  curric:correction """Mai's son was born in Britain, but his cultural identity is important to him and he doesn't feel at home in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-story-takes-place-dark-gloomy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The story takes place in a dark, gloomy and traditionally Gothic setting."@en ;
  curric:correction """Stevenson deliberately juxtaposes the building Hyde enters with the pleasant and well-to-do neighbourhood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.696876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enid-wants-move-back-jamaica
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Enid wants to move back to Jamaica."@en ;
  curric:correction """Enid is full of inner conflict; it is not as simple as wanting to move back to Jamaica, or wanting to stay in England."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697088Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-del-rude-ever-obeah
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Del is as rude as ever about obeah."@en ;
  curric:correction """Del is rude in this scene, but she also asks questions and watches Mai's practices."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697093Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enid-doesnt-think-england-racist
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Enid doesn't think England is racist."@en ;
  curric:correction """Enid is very private about her views: we see only her reaction to the discrimination she faces. Consider if her dialogue reveals more."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697101Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-orwell-offers-solution-problems-explores
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Orwell offers a solution to the problems he explores."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore the idea of "resolution" in terms of 'Animal Farm'. Does Orwell offer any resolutions? Does the story feel finished?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cant-analyse-stage-directions-depth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can't analyse stage directions in depth."@en ;
  curric:correction """The closing stage directions of 'Leave Taking' are integral in understanding Pinnock's final messages about the characters and themes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697767Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sheers-tells-us-couple-arguing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Sheers tells us that the couple have been arguing before heading out for their walk."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Sheers doesn't explicitly tell us that the couple have been arguing but subtly implies this using personification and pathetic fallacy in the first two stanzas. He describes how the couple are "silent and apart" to show their fragmented relationship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-temporal-ellipsis-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that temporal ellipsis is used solely because the playwright wants to avoid showing certain events on stage due to logistical constraints or a desire to avoid graphic scenes."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While practical concerns can influence a playwright’s decision, temporal ellipsis is primarily a deliberate artistic choice to emphasise emotional or psychological consequences over the event itself."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698098Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-wealthy-victorians-feel-bad-living
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Wealthy Victorians did feel bad about those living in poverty but had no power to do anything about it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many wealthy Victorians felt little sympathy for the poor, believing instead that people in poverty were lazy or morally inferior."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698103Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-form-poem-doesnt-influence-our
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the form of a poem doesn't influence our analysis."@en ;
  curric:correction """The chosen form can influence our perception of the theme of a poem and give us a clue into the writer's intentions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698289Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cannot-respected-feared
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You cannot be both respected and feared."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Romantic sublime was the concept that we should feel awe towards nature - a mixture of both fear and respect."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698355Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-believes-control-their-lives
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That everyone believes they have control over their lives."@en ;
  curric:correction "Some people believe that their lives are controlled by fate and destiny."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698399Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-theme-moment-idea-text
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A theme is any moment or idea in a text."@en ;
  curric:correction """A theme is an idea that is explored in multiple different ways - it has to come up more than once in a text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698427Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-war-poems-equally
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may think that all war poems are equally suitable for comparison."@en ;
  curric:correction """Grouping the war poems into distinct categories can help students see the subtle differences between poems that seem to be largely about the same thing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-snowball-isnt-blame-failed-revolution
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Snowball isn't to blame for the failed revolution."@en ;
  curric:correction """How many examples can you find where Snowball supports hierarchical ideas that go against the ideals of equality?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romantics-known-writing-love-romance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Romantics were known for writing about love and romance."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Romantics are not to be confused with 'romantics' who may write love poetry. The Romantics most commonly wrote about nature and were known for critiquing the direction of society's progress."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698446Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-avoid-analysing-structure-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often avoid analysing structure because they sometimes struggle to understand what it actually is and means."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The structure of a text is just how the poem has been put together - what comes where and why. Using the words 'establishes' 'builds on' and 'ends' will encourage students to talk about structure more confidently."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698486Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-quick-identify-poems-rhyme
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students are quick to identify a poem's rhyme scheme, but they often fail to explain its effect or why it has been used."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In this poem, Hardy arguably uses the same rhyme scheme throughout to reflect the inevitability of death and grief as a result of war. The rhyme scheme becomes a pattern in the same way that death and devastation becomes a pattern in war."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698493Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-way-poet-uses-punctuation-poem
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The way a poet uses punctuation in a poem is not useful to analyse."@en ;
  curric:correction """Creating pauses within poetic lines using punctuation, such as caesuras, can create ideas of separation or disjointedness."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698498Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-soldiers-aware-signing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Soldiers were always aware of what they were signing up for."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many men and boys who signed up to fight for the British Empire were unaware of the realities of war and what it would mean for them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-recurring-image-happens-accident-especially
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That a recurring image happens by accident - especially if it's an everyday object then it's likely to be meaningless."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Images are often symbols for deeper meaning in literature - especially everyday, domestic objects and then can represent ideas about the central theme of a text."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698560Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-its-impossible-create-imaginative-similes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That it's impossible to create imaginative similes."@en ;
  curric:correction """While your mind will often go to common similes at first, you can consider how you can use synonyms/antonyms, sensory details, and extra detail in order to create imaginative similes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698565Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-exclamative-sentences-way-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You should use exclamative sentences all the way through your writing to show tension."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It can be more effective to begin with declarative sentences and progress to exclamative sentences to show the rising tension."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698572Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-doesnt-matter-quotations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that it doesn't matter which quotations they select for use."@en ;
  curric:correction """It can be difficult to bring any new interpretations to commonly-used quotations, so try to pick some lesser-used ones."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698577Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-bob-cratchit-represents
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often believe that Bob Cratchit represents the most poor group of people in society."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst Bob Cratchit certainly struggles for money and has to be resourceful to feed his family, he still has a job and a home."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-scrooge-christ-figure
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that Scrooge is a Christ-figure in the novella."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst some parallels are arguably evident between Scrooge and Christ, the idea that Tiny Tim is a Christ-figure is probably more viable."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698586Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-conclusion-your-speech-introduce-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """In the conclusion of your speech, you should introduce one final point that helps to persuade any audience members who haven't been convinced throughout your speech."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Your conclusion isn't really the place to introduce new ideas as it will be tricky for you to fully develop them before you finish speaking. Instead, use the conclusion to summarise your key ideas and reinforce your central message."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698623Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-considering-description-students-focus-external
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "When considering description, students often focus on the external effect."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ask how things might look different depending on your personality or circumstances? Offer examples e.g. how a town might be described differently by someone who enjoys living there and someone who dislikes living there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-initially-link-examples-personification
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may not initially link all of the examples of personification together."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that finding patterns in the text can be very useful to help create a thoughtful idea about the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698634Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lines-know-knew-thee-knew
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The lines, "They know not I knew thee, / Who knew thee too well" refer to the close emotional relationship the couple had since they knew everything about each other."""@en ;
  curric:correction """These lines can also be read as a euphemism for the couple's sexual relationship, since 'know' was a term often used in the Bible to refer to sexual intercourse."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698641Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-solely-directed-silent-listener
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The poem is solely directed at the silent listener ("yu") who is addressed in the opening of the poem."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It could be argued that this silent listener could symbolise all readers (or listeners) of this poem since the speaker discusses how they will behave when they are "introduced" to the "yu" figure, implying they haven't yet met."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698645Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-generally-believe-free
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That people generally believe in free will and always have."@en ;
  curric:correction """In Elizabethan England, people typically believed that fate controlled their lives - they believed they did not have free will."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-character-important-setting-trying-solve
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Character is more important than setting when trying to solve mystery."@en ;
  curric:correction """Jekyll tells Utterson there is nothing he should worry about - this is not true. Ask pupils how the setting indicates that Jekyll is lying."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-language-devices-like-extended-analogies
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Language devices - like extended analogies - are more appropriate for analysis in stories and narrative fiction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Using language devices such as extended analogies can be a very effective way of communicating ideas in non-fiction writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698680Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-confuse-analogies-other-comparative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may confuse analogies with other comparative based figures of speech such as simile and metaphor."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage students to think of students as an extended example and the core purpose is explanation not the evocation of associations and related imagery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698685Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-best-analysis-identifies-similarities-differences
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The best analysis identifies similarities and differences between poems in the anthology."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The best analysis will look for nuanced variations between similarities (e.g. 'Both 'Bayonet Charge' and 'Remains' explore the impact of war on individuals. However, Remains focuses more on war's aftermath and the psychological effect it can have.')"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698689Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romantic-literature-love-romance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Romantic literature is about love and romance."@en ;
  curric:correction """Romantic literature is concerned with human emotion but Romanticism was a movement that rejected the principles of the Enlightenment period."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698694Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-snowball-really-responsible-windmill-collapsing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That Snowball really is responsible for the windmill collapsing and other events on the farm."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore the question, how do you know if propaganda is working effectively? When there is unwavering belief in its messages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-tend-confuse-tone-mood
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students tend to confuse tone and mood. They are not the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Tone is the way in which the poet expresses their feelings towards the subject matter. Mood is the atmosphere that is created by the tone. Tone creates mood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698703Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-brods-drinking-appropriate-meant-funny
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Brod's drinking is appropriate and meant to be funny."@en ;
  curric:correction """Both Enid and Del challenge Brod's drinking, and his scenes expose his unhappiness, isolation and vulnerability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698724Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparative-responses-list-similarities-differences
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Comparative responses are just a list of similarities and differences."@en ;
  curric:correction """While identifying similarities and differences is essential, your comparative response should also articulate a clear argument that ties these observations together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698741Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poems-consider-speakers-individual-feelings
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That poems always consider the speaker's individual feelings and emotions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Poems often use the speaker as a way of observing life around them and commenting on wider society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698746Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-get-definitive-idea-writers-intentions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "We can get a definitive idea of the writer's intentions from the text."@en ;
  curric:correction """We can never truly know what the writer's intentions were but we can tentatively explore ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lady-macbeths-presentation-same-act
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lady Macbeth's presentation is the same in both Act 1, Scene 5 and Scene 7."@en ;
  curric:correction "There is an increase in urgency, violence and strategy in Act 1, Scene 7."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698767Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-henry-jekyll-responsible-death-mr
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Henry Jekyll is responsible for the death of Mr. Hyde. Jekyll is the 'self-destroyer.'"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Hyde uses Jekyll as his protection from the gallows. When Jekyll is no more, it is Hyde who chooses death over punishment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698772Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stevenson-extremely-critical-science
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Stevenson was extremely critical of science."@en ;
  curric:correction """Stevenson certainly plays on contemporary fears over unfettered scientific development. Whilst his novella could be seen as a criticism of this, the extent to which which Stevenson uses the text as his own personal criticism is arguable."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mr-utterson-judgemental-immoral-behaviour
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mr. Utterson is judgemental of all immoral behaviour."@en ;
  curric:correction """Mr. Utterson seems incredibly judgemental of the Victorian poor and their behaviour but he is willing to turn a 'blind eye' to his friends."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speakers-foe-poisoned-fruit-grew
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The speaker's foe was poisoned by the fruit he grew."@en ;
  curric:correction """At the beginning of the poem, the speaker seems to imply that the tree is metaphorical since it "grew" from the speaker's anger and resentment so perhaps the death of the "foe" could symbolise another sort of revenge undertaken by the speaker."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-refugees-come-places-war-torn
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That refugees come from places that have always been war torn and a disaster zone."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Refugees can come from anywhere - places that used to be beautiful but have changed through war, regime change or natural disaster."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698793Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-economic-migrant-refugee-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That an economic migrant and a refugee are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """A refugee is someone who has been forced to leave their country in order to escape war, persecution or natural disaster."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698804Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-brod-patriotic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Brod has never been patriotic."@en ;
  curric:correction """Brod expresses that he loved and respected England until his naturalisation process which destabilised his sense of self and opened his eyes to some of the injustices he faces, in his present and his past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698809Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-use-context-bolt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students often use context as a 'bolt-on'."@en ;
  curric:correction """Context is a valuable additional source of evidence for your argument. Context should be relevant, specific and support your argument. It should be 'peppered' throughout your essay and not 'bolted-on' at the end."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698821Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-napoleon-old-major-completely-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Napoleon and Old Major are completely different."@en ;
  curric:correction """Look closely at their speeches. Interestingly they are very similar in their uses of devices, delivery and how they motivate the animals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698830Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-windrush-generation-illegal-migrants
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Windrush generation were illegal migrants."@en ;
  curric:correction "Those coming from the British Commonwealth were considered citizens."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698834Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-context-mentioned-separately
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think context should be mentioned separately at the end of their paragraphs, rather than integrated throughout their analysis."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Context should be woven into your analysis to enrich your interpretation e.g. 'Nagra's depiction of family duties versus personal desires draws from his British-Indian experience, showcasing challenges faced by second-generation immigrants.'"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698863Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-brooke-fought-died
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might think that Brooke fought and died in the war because he wrote a war poem."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Brooke bravely volunteered to fight in the war, he never actually engaged in any military action. Unfortunately, Brooke died from septicaemia on a ship en route to battle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698868Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-brooke-fought-died
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that Brooke fought and died in the war because he wrote a war poem."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Brooke bravely volunteered to fight in the war, he never actually engaged in any military action. Unfortunately, Brooke died from septicaemia on a ship en route to battle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-speaker-mourns-their-lover
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "In this poem, the speaker mourns for their lover after they have died."@en ;
  curric:correction """This could be a valid interpretation but there is no evidence to suggest the lover is definitely dead. In fact, the volta in L.9 has the speaker demand he return which implies that there is a chance they could be reunited with one another."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698877Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-farmer-simply-trying-care-his
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The farmer is simply trying to care for his wife, his actions are well-intentioned and innocent."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The farmer's attempts to care for his wife may initially seem genuine, but the poem suggests a deeper complexity to their relationship. The bride's evident distress and desire to escape challenge the notion of the farmer's benevolence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698893Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romantic-poems-anthology-equally-comparable
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Romantic poems from the anthology are equally comparable."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some Romantic poems are more suitable for comparison, depending on which question you are asked."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698898Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-clear-message-togetherness-division
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "This poem has a clear message about togetherness and division."@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem is an abstract exploration of the different ways divisions and togetherness affect our relationships with each other (both personal relationships and our relationships in society)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-idleness-means-laziness
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That idleness means laziness."@en ;
  curric:correction "Idleness can also mean enjoying periods of rest and relaxation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-fail-recognise-tense-shifts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students sometimes fail to recognise that the tense shifts as the poem progresses."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Owen includes three tenses in his poem, perhaps to illustrate that the impact of war has, is and will be felt in his past, present and future."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-larkin-hostile-relationship
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often think that Larkin must have had a hostile relationship with his family because of this poem and some of his other poems."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Larkin didn't have a hostile relationship with his parents - he was just a cynical man who held quite bleak views. This doesn't mean he hated his parents - he just recognised that people are products of their own parents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698957Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-essay-introductions-focus-heavily-poets
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Essay introductions should focus heavily on the poets and/or literary devices."@en ;
  curric:correction """Essay introductions should focus heavily on big ideas relevant to both poems and related to the question."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-conflict-refers-physical-conflict-e
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Conflict only refers to physical conflict e.g. war"@en ;
  curric:correction "Conflict can be psychological, moral and between ideas, not just physical."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699024Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-specific-historical-event-fact
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Context has to be a specific historical event or fact."@en ;
  curric:correction """Considering the themes in the poet's other work is a valuable consideration of context."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699028Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-poem-unrequited-romantic-feelings
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The speaker of the poem has unrequited romantic feelings for the man and yearns to be with him."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This is only one interpretation of the poem. Alternatively, the reference to "romance" in L.5 could imply that the speaker romanticises the natural world that she is so distanced from in her urban landscape and yearns to return to nature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-anthology-explores-title-theme
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That an anthology only explores the title theme."@en ;
  curric:correction """An anthology could also explore the inverse of the title theme in order to highlight particular ideas or concepts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699038Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ambivalence-means-care-either-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Ambivalence means you do not care either way (similar to indifference)."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ambivalence is when someone has mixed or conflicting feelings about something or someone."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699073Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-meaning-poem-remains-static-throughout
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the meaning of a poem remains static throughout."@en ;
  curric:correction """In 'Homing', the subject's accent is portrayed as something negative at the beginning of the poem. However, by the end it is portrayed as something vital to identity and heritage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-poem-wants-everyone-tolerant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The speaker of the poem wants everyone to be more tolerant and united."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although the speaker does claim to want this, he does also confess that he finds it challenging at times, especially when it comes to his personal relationship with "you"."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699120Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romantic-poems-present-nature-positive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Romantic poems always present nature in a positive light."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sometimes Romantic poets may show the devastation that humanity has caused nature or talk about nature in a grieving way."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699124Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-asked-answer-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students might think that they will only be asked to answer one poetry question."@en ;
  curric:correction """The examination requires students to answer 2 questions: the first one is an analysis of a single poem; the second one is a comparison question."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699131Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-long-include-quotations-poems-mention
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """As long as I include quotations from both poems and mention some similarities or differences, I’m doing a good comparative analysis."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Without analysis, the response does not explain how or why the poets present their ideas, or what effects those choices have. This limits the depth and quality of the comparison."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699138Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-doesnt-rhyme
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poem doesn't rhyme."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although the poem doesn't follow a conventional and predictable rhyme scheme, it does have some irregular and half rhymes (e.g. "chapatti" and "chutney"). This structure imitates the playful and joyous content of the poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699166Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-kills-porphyria-love-his
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The speaker kills Porphyria out of love, and his actions can be seen as a romantic gesture."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The speaker's actions aren't a romantic gesture but a sign of his disturbed mind. His love is possessive and obsessive, shown by his desire to control Porphyria. The calm tone he uses to describe the murder show his detachment from reality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699173Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-romantics-wrote-nature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the Romantics only wrote about nature."@en ;
  curric:correction "Often Romantic writers also wrote about a nostalgia for the past."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699180Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-fail-recognise-arguably-poem
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may fail to recognise that arguably, this poem is a series of stories instead of one 'big' story."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Dove arguably tells several small stories which all contribute to our understanding of the depth of love between her and her husband - Fred."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699185Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-comparative-topic-sentence-focus-differences
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A comparative topic sentence should only focus on the differences between poems."@en ;
  curric:correction """A comparative topic sentence should either state the similarities or differences between the poems in relation to the central focus of the paragraph."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699189Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-good-pigs-bad-pigs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That there are \"good\" pigs and \"bad\" pigs."@en ;
  curric:correction """For Orwell, all are susceptible to power and corruption. Orwell uses the pigs to critique the subtle and overt ways that this can be done."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699231Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quotes-need-long
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That quotes need to be long."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore the purpose of quotes and how efficiency is key. What is considered an effective use of quotes?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699296Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-planning-takes-long
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Planning takes too long."@en ;
  curric:correction """A detailed plan will speed up the writing process and ensure a cohesive and well structured argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-write-reassuring-resolution-need-tie
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That to write a reassuring resolution all you need to do is tie the narrative points together."""@en ;
  curric:correction """To craft a reassuring resolution then you might think about how you can use imagery, symbolism and figurative language to convey calm emotions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699549Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-counter-arguments-throughout-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Using counter-arguments throughout your essay makes it a stronger argument."@en ;
  curric:correction """You should have one clear, critical response to the question that informs your whole essay."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699572Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-production-play-same-because-plays
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Each production of a play is the same because the play's script is always the same."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The production of a play is always unique. The choice of director, producer, theatre, cast and the nature of its audiences all contribute."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699600Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-benefit-looking-other-peoples-responses
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is no benefit in looking at other people's responses."@en ;
  curric:correction """How do you feel looking at your own work? It is quite difficult to be critical of your own work, practising on model essays helps this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699605Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-feel-negatively-towards-rituals
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the animals feel negatively towards the rituals and ideas put forward by the pigs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Think about the response to Beasts of England. Is this same atmosphere created by Napoleon's parade? Why are the pigs' rituals different?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quotes-essays-need-long-difficult
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That quotes in essays need to be long and are difficult to remember."@en ;
  curric:correction """Can you remember anything Boxer says? How about words used to describe characters? Any of the commandments? These are all key quotes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699616Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-work-hard-enough-escape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "People who work hard enough can escape poverty."@en ;
  curric:correction """This was a common belief in Victorian times when people in poverty faced much social stigma. Unfortunately, poverty was not easy to escape; many poor people were uneducated, had no access to healthcare and lived in cramped conditions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-del-hates-education-system-school
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Del hates the education system and school."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst Del did not have a positive school experience, she knows the value of education, hence her extreme reaction to Viv skipping an exam."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699649Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-revolution-complete-failure
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the revolution is a complete failure."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explore the quote "the farm was more prosperous now, and better organised". Who has benefitted? Would some consider this a success?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-priestley-suggests-gender-roles-successfully
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Priestley suggests that all gender roles have been successfully challenged by the end of the play."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A more nuanced view is that argaubly Priestley shows both progress and resistance, suggesting that while some characters challenge gender roles, societal change is slow and not fully realised."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699698Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-george-orwell-communist
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "George Orwell was a communist."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Orwell wanted an equal society, he viewed communism as corruptible and idealistic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-enids-life-jamaica-terrible-wasnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Enid's life in Jamaica was terrible. It wasn't hard for her to leave."@en ;
  curric:correction """Enid faced limited opportunities in Jamaica, but leaving also meant she forever altered her relationships with her family and community."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699720Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-equally-responsible-defence-animal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All animals were equally responsible for the defence of Animal Farm."@en ;
  curric:correction """Snowball and Boxer were instrumental in the victory. Mollie deliberately shied away and Napoleon was curiously unmentioned."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699725Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-play-set-series-days-dels
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The play is set over a series of days so Del's character development is rapid."@en ;
  curric:correction """The stage directions at the beginning of each scene show that sometimes a few days have past, and sometimes much longer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pigs-immediately-set-taking-control
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The pigs immediately set about taking control of the farm."@en ;
  curric:correction """The pigs' increasing power and control is a gradual process, relying on incremental changes in the commandments to gain overall control."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-happy-work-sacrifices-making
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the animals are happy in the work and with the sacrifices they are making."@en ;
  curric:correction """Link back to Orwell's purpose about manipulation and propaganda. Their reality does not match the promises of the revolution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quotation-write-analysed-detail
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Every quotation you write about should be analysed in detail."@en ;
  curric:correction """Main quotations should be analysed, but you should also include supporting quotations that are embedded into sentences without analysis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poems-purely-works-imagination
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Poems are purely works of imagination."@en ;
  curric:correction """While poems draw on the poet's imagination, many poems are drawn from real-life experiences which is why there is such an emotional resonance in them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rhetorical-devices-same-effect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Rhetorical devices always have the same effect."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although we can make some assumptions about the effect of devices, considering specific information like the writer's intention and form will give a much more detailed and nuanced explanation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-same-metaphysical-understanding-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That we all have the same metaphysical understanding of time."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some people consider time to be linear, Seneviratne arguably considers time to be cyclical."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-contrast-poem-intended-show
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the use of contrast in a poem is always intended to show friction and tension."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While the use of contrast shows difference, it doesn't necessarily have to show friction; instead, it might represent how we can coexist even though we are different."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-war-links-conflict-solely-due
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """War links to conflict solely due to the violence and brutality between opposing sides whilst fighting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """War can also link to mental conflict long after the fighting is done as we see in Armitage's poem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699927Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-natural-imagery-links-relationship-humanity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That natural imagery always links to the relationship between humanity and the environment."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Natural imagery can also be used to show that a concept or idea is natural or that it is flourishing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699936Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-poet-support-idea
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might think that the poet does not support the idea of love."@en ;
  curric:correction """In the poem, the speaker is expressing their love for their partner. The speaker does support love, and acknowledges the benefits it can bring - they just also acknowledge the great harm it can cause."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699941Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-mourns-growing-distance-him
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The speaker mourns the growing distance between him and his mother."@en ;
  curric:correction """This is just one interpretation of the text; we could also infer that the speaker has felt stifled by their mother's involvement in their life until now and yearns for their independence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699957Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-three-poems-reflect-memories-loved
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All three poems reflect on memories of a loved one who is now dead."@en ;
  curric:correction """Causley's use of an uncanny setting implies that the two parents are now in the afterlife, guiding the speaker's "[c]rossing", however Duffy and Waterhouse use language linked to death/loss ("ghost", "pulse") but do not imply the relative has died."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699967Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-focus-entirely-similarities-differences-writing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That you should focus entirely on similarities or differences when writing a comparative response."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When writing a comparative response, you should consider the overarching similarities and then consider the subtle differences within the similarities to create a nuanced response."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699985Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-discuss-similarities-differences
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students think that they can only discuss the similarities OR the differences between poems."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Though they should approach the comparison by identifying key or significant similarities or difference, within that, they can also explore the subtle variations between poems too."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-woman-poem-didnt-love-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The woman in the poem didn't love her baby because she abandoned them when the bomb went off."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It's difficult to hold someone to account for their actions in  a traumatic event like this. Furthermore, the description of the "burden" the woman abandons could also be interpreted as an emotional burden that the shock causes her to leave behind."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700034Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-poets-try-make
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students sometimes think that poets always try to make their poems sound pleasing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Poets may use harsh or disagreeable sounds within their poetry in order to emphasise meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-war-poems-anthology-equally-comparable
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All war poems from the anthology are equally comparable."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some war poems are more suitable for comparison, depending on which question you are asked. You should make your decision based on which ideas and themes you want to discuss."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700048Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-hughes-wrote-poem
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that Hughes wrote this poem about fascist dictators like Hitler."@en ;
  curric:correction """Hughes stated that this was not his intention. Though the poem can be interpreted in this way, this was not what Hughes set out to convey - he wanted to convey the power of nature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700053Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-single-clear-interpretation-tissue
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is a single, clear interpretation of 'Tissue'."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are varied interpretations of the poem and - as long as they are supported by evidence - they are valid. Students may focus on the comparison of power to paper or on the similar fragility between paper and human life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700079Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-zoom-suffering-within-photos
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may zoom into the suffering within the photos and not realise the complex emotions in the photographer himself."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Duffy, having seen  her friends do the job of photojournalism, may have been privy to the complex and difficult emotions involved in this job. This could be why she focuses on the quiet trauma within the photographer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700085Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poetry-war-based-first-hand
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Poetry about war is always based on first-hand experience."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many poems about war are from the perspective of family members who are also impacted by their loved ones going to war."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700090Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-understand-concept-photo-developing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may not understand the concept of photo developing when initially reading the poem and thus not realise what the poem is about."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain the process of photo developing film photographs in a dark room - the dark room is because photographs are light-sensitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-outlining-similarity-two-poems-sufficient
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Outlining a similarity between two poems is sufficient to compare."@en ;
  curric:correction """If you want to improve your work and ensure it is 'critical', you must interrogate the subtle differences between poems."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700099Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-considers-time-linear-moving
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That everyone considers time to be linear: moving from past, to present, to the future."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many works of literature consider time to be cyclical and consider us to be repeating or echoing what has happened in the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700106Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-initially-notice-structural-choices
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may not initially notice the structural choices within the poem such as tense and enjambment."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain how language, structure, perspective and tense are always constructed meaningfully by the poet to match their purpose."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700124Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-apparent-support-pigs-genuine
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The animals' apparent support for the pigs is genuine loyalty."@en ;
  curric:correction """The reality is that this is manipulation, fear, and the pigs' gradual control over them. Examine the pigs' tactics."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700134Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-eden-rock-real-place
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Eden Rock is a real place."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eden Rock is a fictional place, devised by the poet Charles Causley. Causley confirms this but does suggest that he based the location on the Cornish landscape where he grew up."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700171Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-dharker-critical-structures
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that Dharker is critical of the structures in the slums."@en ;
  curric:correction """Though Dharker portrays how dangerous these buildings are, she also shows great admiration of the slum community's resourcefulness in building theses structures - she celebrates their fortitude and resilience in the face of adversity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700176Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-decide-one-main-interpretation-text
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You should decide on one main interpretation of text and focus on that in your analytical writing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Effective analytical writing often includes multiple interpretations of a text and careful consideration of the wider context."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poet-doesnt-conform-poetic-form
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "If a poet doesn't conform to a poetic form then they are rejecting it."@en ;
  curric:correction """By not using a particular poetic form, or subverting a poetic form, a poet may be critiquing a certain expectation or making a certain comment on society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700195Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-silence-negative-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That silence is a negative thing."@en ;
  curric:correction "Silence can also be peaceful, enriching and calming."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysis-paragraph-link-wider-context
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Every analysis paragraph should link to the wider context."@en ;
  curric:correction """Effective analysis links to context only when relevant to the discussion of key ideas/methods and avoids 'bolt-on' sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700218Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-del-uninterested-obeah-until-mai
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Del is uninterested in obeah until Mai realises it is her calling."@en ;
  curric:correction "Del's interest in obeah is foreshadowed from Scene One onwards."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700228Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-equal-even-start
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the animals are always equal, even from the very start."@en ;
  curric:correction """Focus on the positioning of the animals and how they enter the barn. Orwell is already beginning to make distinctions between the animals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700234Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-brod-religious
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Brod is not religious."@en ;
  curric:correction "Consider the admiration Brod has for Pastor Chully Johnson."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700239Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-content-poem-matters-speaking-poem
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The content of the poem matters more than who is speaking in the poem."@en ;
  curric:correction """The voice we hear in a poem is incredibly important for the meaning as it could show us who the poet deems as important or perhaps they are making a comment on who has agency in society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700267Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-written-form-sonnet-14
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """This poem is written in the form of a sonnet: it has 14 lines and a regular rhyme scheme."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem does not strictly follow the sonnet form but does use many of its conventions. It contains 15, not 14 lines and doesn't use a regular rhyme scheme. It does however end with a rhyming couplet and uses iambic pentameter in places."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700276Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-entire-poem-rhyming
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students think that the entire poem is in rhyming couplets."@en ;
  curric:correction """Only the beginning of the poem is written in rhyming couplets. The couplets fade to pararhymes and then to non-rhyming couplets by the end of the poem, possibly to reflect the soldier's pain fading and the healing process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-initially-see-natural-imagery
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may not initially see the natural imagery as relevant."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to students that Ted Hughes was famous for his nature and animal poetry. He would have included these themes deliberately with a strong sense of purpose."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700314Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysis-paragraphs-lead-feature-spotting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Analysis paragraphs should lead by 'feature-spotting' a technique and then linking it to key ideas."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The most effective analysis paragraphs lead with key ideas supported by evidence from the text, analysis of writer's methods, a justification of ideas and a link to the writer's intentions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700318Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-compare-two-poems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students might think that they can only compare two poems from the same thematic cluster within the anthology."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Students can compare any pair of poems as long as the poems have some similarities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700323Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thesis-statements-topic-sentences-synonymous
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Thesis statements and topic sentences are synonymous."@en ;
  curric:correction """Thesis statements are supported by the whole text. Topic sentences give direction and purpose to individual paragraphs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700335Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-napoleons-move-towards-autocracy-sudden
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Napoleon's move towards autocracy is a sudden process."@en ;
  curric:correction """It is gradual. Each chapter sees the spirit of the revolution and 'Animalism' further degraded by the actions of Napoleon and the pigs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700340Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-context-cant-included-topic-sentence
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Context can't be included in a topic sentence or analysis. It must be confined to its own sentences."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Context can be woven into any moment in a paragraph; you must decide where it will be most purposeful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700372Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analysing-poem-students-use-terminology
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When analysing this poem, students might not use terminology as well as they could."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Heaney uses a lot of onomatopoeia in his descriptions within this poem, as well as semantic fields and figurative language."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700399Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-regular-repetitive-structure-nine
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The poem has a regular, repetitive structure of nine, unrhyming quatrains."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although most of the poem is written in this way, there is a sudden and sharp break to this form with the final stanza being a single line. You may wish to discuss this with your class (learning cycle 2 discusses the significance of this break)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700413Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-recognise-hawk-powerful-dont
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students recognise that the hawk is powerful and don't explore this any further."@en ;
  curric:correction """The significant question in the poem is arguably what makes the hawk powerful? Is it nature? Instinct? His physical strength? His intelligence?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700418Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-fail-appreciate-significance-speaker
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often fail to appreciate the significance of the speaker being the soldier's wife."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The perspective the poem is written from is deeply significant. Perhaps Armitage chose to write the poem from the perspective of the wife because the soldier is too traumatised to speak of his own experiences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700448Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-heard-folk-tales-nursery
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may have not heard of the folk tales and nursery rhymes in the poem so may not be able to identify them as such."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The use of nursery rhymes and folk tale was a deliberate stylistic choice, perhaps Agard is indignant about the trivial nature of some of his education."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700457Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-order-words-poem-random-unimportant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the order of words in a poem is random and unimportant."@en ;
  curric:correction """The order of words creates a journey and progression through the poem which can influence the overall message."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700464Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-interpretation-poem-storm-island
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is only one interpretation of the poem 'Storm on the Island'."@en ;
  curric:correction """The poem can be a reflection of the power of nature, conflict between humans and nature, the political conflict or all."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700485Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-last-two-lines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that in the last two lines of the poem, the father now follows behind the son while he is out ploughing a field."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although their roles have reversed, there is no indication that the last two lines involve the father and son ploughing. The echoes in the language merely symbolise that their roles have reversed as the son has grown up."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700490Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-fail-recognise-poem-itself
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students fail to recognise that the poem itself is a kind of memorial for the 38th division in the Battle of Mametz Wood."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The poem immortalises the Welsh soldiers in the 38th division, who lay undiscovered for decades, their stories untold. In this sense, the poem itself has become these soldiers' legacy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700506Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-autobiographical-account-one-heaneys
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "This poem is an autobiographical account of one of Heaney's childhood memories."@en ;
  curric:correction """This collection, 'Death of Naturalist', is semi-autobiographical since it reflects on aspects of Heaney's childhood, growing up in a rural Irish farming community, but the poet has never confirmed that this particular memory is from his childhood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700531Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stylistic-choices-poem-harmony-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All stylistic choices in a poem have to be in harmony with each other."@en ;
  curric:correction """Heaney's stylistic choices often seem to contradict each other but this could be symbolic of the conflict occurring between man and nature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700559Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-philosophical-ideas-time-bearing-literature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That philosophical ideas of time have no bearing on literature."@en ;
  curric:correction """Considering the nature of time impacts the human experience and therefore has a bearing on literature since it explores what it means to be human."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700583Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-focuses-moral-complexities-war
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "This poem focuses on the moral complexities of war and conflict."@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem is less about war and more about the stories we tell/hear/see about it. Arguably, Satyamurti suggests that there is no way to fully capture traumatic experiences like this since neither the picture nor caption capture what really happened."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700588Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-speaker-love-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils think that the speaker does not love their partner very much."@en ;
  curric:correction """The speaker does love their partner - very much. The speaker, unlike other lovers, refuses to make promises that they aren't 100% sure they can't keep - they arguably find promising 'forever' unrealistic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700592Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-make-mistake-thinking-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students often make the mistake of thinking that, like many of the other war poems, this poem was written by a soldier at the time of the war."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This poem is not a personal account; Sheers wrote this poem in 2005. He wanted to raise awareness about the loss of Welsh lives in Mametz Wood and illustrate how destructive war is."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-brod-enids-husband
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Brod is Enid's husband."@en ;
  curric:correction """Brod is a family friend. Enid's husband is mentioned in the play, but he left her and his two children when they were little."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700609Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poem-one-meaning
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That a poem has only one meaning."@en ;
  curric:correction """A poem can have many different meanings woven together because we are all made up of different ideas and our views on the world are rarely singular."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700627Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-idea-paradise-same-everyone
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the idea of \"paradise\" is the same for everyone."@en ;
  curric:correction """We all have our own concept of what "paradise" looks like and what it might mean in terms of our memories and connections to the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700646Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-write-poem-separately
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you should write about each poem separately."@en ;
  curric:correction """While writing about one poem at a time is one way to approach a comparison, it's usually more effective to weave your comparisons of the poems through the whole answer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700654Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-its-important-include-contextual-link
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It's important to include a contextual link in every analytical paragraph."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although it is important to include links to wider context in your overall response, it isn't necessary to include a contextual link in every analytical paragraph. In fact, 'bolt-on' contextual links should be avoided."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700670Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-speaker-explains-children-ruined-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The speaker explains how having children ruined her mother's life."@en ;
  curric:correction """While Duffy does explore how motherhood has contributed to her mother's loss of confidence and freedom, the final stanza of the poem shows them both having fun together so it is evident that there are many positive aspects to motherhood as well."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700682Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-agard-went-school
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that Agard went to school in Britain and that is the reason for his Eurocentric education."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Agard was schooled in Guyana whilst it was a British colony, this is the reason for his Eurocentric education. Learning about the colonisation of Guyana can help students to understand Agard's indignation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700701Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-right-answer-comes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students sometimes think there is a 'right' answer when it comes to poetry - that the poem has to have one meaning."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The beauty of poetry is that it means something different to everybody - there is no 'right' answer - there are a series of possible answers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-narrative-voice-animal-farm-reports
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The narrative voice of 'Animal Farm' reports the truth to the reader."@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, the narrative voice withholds information about the pig's oppressive behaviour."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701110Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-characters-either-conform-subvert-stereotypes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That characters either conform to or subvert stereotypes within texts."@en ;
  curric:correction """We might see Romeo and Juliet as both conforming to and subverting societal expectations of gender at different moments in 'Romeo and Juliet' - characters are typically multifaceted rather than one note."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-blood-symbolises-violence-bloodshed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Blood only symbolises violence and bloodshed."@en ;
  curric:correction "Blood comes to symbolise psychological turmoil and guilt as the play progresses."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701459Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-light-referenced-significant-macbeths-stars
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Light is only referenced and significant in Macbeth's 'Stars, hide your fires' soliloquy taken from Act 1, Scene 4."""@en ;
  curric:correction """If we look closely at what could be considered 'minor' scenes in the play, we can begin to build a clear and nuanced idea of the motif of light throughout."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701463Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cliffhangers-designed-make-reader-carry
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That cliffhangers are only designed to make the reader carry on reading."@en ;
  curric:correction """Cliffhangers can entice the reader to continue reading, but they can also create tension and subvert the reader's expectations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-enids-flat-straightforward
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may believe that Enid's flat is a straightforward symbol of her success and assimilation into British culture, ignoring its role as a site of personal and cultural conflict."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that while the flat does represent Enid's material success it is also the site of many of the play's conflicts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.702762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-content-your-argument-makes-persuasive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It is the content of your argument that makes it persuasive rather than the construction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The way you construct your argument directly impacts how persuasive it is to the reader."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.702794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-turning-point-play
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that a turning point in a play only involves a major event, such as a character's death, without recognising the emotional or relational changes that accompany it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It’s important to clarify that a turning point not only indicates a significant event but also involves the emotional and relational dynamics of the characters e.g. the emotional aftermath of Mooma's death as well as the event itself."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.702799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-mais-bedsit-negative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may assume Mai’s bedsit is only a negative symbol of her failure to integrate into British society."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Highlight that while the bedsit represents her struggles, it also serves as a place of support and stability for other characters, symbolising her resilience and strength."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703074Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-personification-effective-your-writing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any use of personification will be effective in your writing."@en ;
  curric:correction """In order to be effective, personification has to evoke a response that will make the reader feel persuaded by your argument."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703356Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plot-twists-typically-reveal-something
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Plot twists typically reveal something hidden about a character."@en ;
  curric:correction """While plot twists may reveal something hidden about a character, plot twists can be used to subvert our expectations of life and resolution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703360Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-guilt-observable-macbeth-lady-macbeth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Guilt is only observable in Macbeth and Lady Macbeth after the murder of King Duncan."""@en ;
  curric:correction """We can look at early scenes in the play through the lens of guilt since Shakespeare has a clear motive for centering the play on guilt."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703365Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-connection-subject-object-sentence-doesnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the connection between the subject and object of a sentence doesn't matter in persuasive writing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Using active or passive voice can affect the tone of your writing and how the reader responds to it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703371Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-language-cannot-alter-see-someone
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Language cannot alter how you see someone else."@en ;
  curric:correction """Alienating and divisive language can be used to create the perception that someone is an outsider and separate from our social group."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inspector-interpreted-representing-absolute-truth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Inspector can only be interpreted as representing absolute truth, as he always speaks with authority and moral certainty."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Inspector may not represent absolute truth. He selectively reveals information and uses moral rhetoric, which could suggest he's guiding the audience toward a particular interpretation of events."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704150Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-characters-view-jamaica
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that all characters view Jamaica as an idealised homeland."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that while Brod and Mai idealise Jamaica, Enid's more cynical view highlights the hardships she faced there, creating tension between characters' perspectives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704158Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-think-crime-fiction-trivial
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some people think that crime fiction is a trivial genre."@en ;
  curric:correction """Crime fiction explores the dark side of human psychology and reading crime fiction where the crime is solved can help reassure us that society is a safe place and criminals are punished."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704306Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-anti-climaxes-disappointing-reader
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That anti-climaxes are always disappointing to the reader."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some people may find them disappointing, they can also be useful in teaching us something about our own expectations around endings and resolutions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704652Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-role-audience-member-isnt-particularly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The role of an audience member isn't particularly important."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise the power of a supportive and respectful audience. Being an encouraging audience member can help peers succeed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dickens-aims-shame-his-wealthy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Dickens aims to shame his wealthy readers into showing compassion by demonstrating that poor people cannot enjoy Christmas because of the poverty they are forced to live in."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While Dickens does use the novella to encourage his readers to show compassion, his depictions of poor people do show them enjoying Christmas. In fact, we could argue poorer characters seem happier because they are able to enjoy simple pleasures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705035Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-choosing-topic-choose-something-personal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "When choosing a topic, you should not choose something personal to focus on."@en ;
  curric:correction """Choosing something meaningful and personal can help you to find and develop your authentic voice. It's all about ensuring you talk about the topic in enough detail and complexity, regardless of what you choose."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705039Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-stage-directions-written
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may believe that the stage directions are written by whoever is putting on a production of the play."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although there is some interpretation of how an actor peforms a scene, the stage directions will have been written by the playwright as part of the script."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705046Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-mistakenly-believe-generational-conflict
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might mistakenly believe that generational conflict only refers to disagreements between parents and children, overlooking the broader societal influences that shape the conflict."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Generational conflict in 'Leave Taking' isn't just about family disagreements; it is also influenced by the different social, cultural, and historical experiences that shape each generation’s view of identity and belonging."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705342Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-priestley-wrote-inspector-calls-solely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Priestley wrote 'An Inspector Calls' solely to change the views of his audience."@en ;
  curric:correction """While it may seem that Priestley wrote 'An Inspector Calls' solely to change the views of his audience, it could also be argued that a 1945 audience would lean towards socialist ideals and therefore his play aimed to solidify these views."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705628Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-analytical-paragraphs-lead-identifying-writer
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Analytical paragraphs should lead by identifying how a writer uses language, form and/or structure."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The best analytical writing begins by exploring how key ideas or attitudes in a poem link to the question focus, supported by analysis of how the writer uses language, form and/or structure to convey these ideas or attitudes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stick-single-interpretation-approach-throughout
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You must stick to a single interpretation or approach throughout your essay to make a strong argument."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst you should have an overarching argument, embracing nuance by exploring multiple interpretations deepens your analysis. This approach strengthens your argument by showing the text’s complexity and layers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706375Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-concept-truth-something-cannot-changed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The concept of truth is something that cannot be changed."@en ;
  curric:correction "Our perception of what it true can be altered by those around us."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706462Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-interpretation-orwells-animal-farm-pigs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The only interpretation of Orwell's 'Animal Farm' is that the pigs' desire for power leads to the animals' oppression."""@en ;
  curric:correction """We might also interpret the animals as being complicit in allowing their oppression to happen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706467Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-doesnt-matter-end-story-people
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It doesn't matter how you end a story - people will have the same emotional reaction."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The way that you end a story drastically impacts the lasting emotional impression and how a reader interprets the story."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706746Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-interpret-friar-lawrence-mentor-figure
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That we can only interpret Friar Lawrence as a mentor figure to Romeo."@en ;
  curric:correction """Though Friar Lawrence offers Romeo advice, we might also see his portrayal in a more negative light."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706755Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-wealth-alone-guaranteed-high-social
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Wealth alone guaranteed a high social status in Victorian society."@en ;
  curric:correction """While wealth was important to securing high social status, reputation was extremely important to wealthy Victorians. Arranged marriages and inheritance were key levers to ensure a good family reputation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-play-definitely-brechtian-purely-social
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The play is definitely Brechtian or purely social realism."@en ;
  curric:correction """The ideas behind Brechtian theatre and social realism were part of the cultural landscape when Priestley was writing. Instead of fitting it into one category, it’s better to consider how Priestley may have been influenced by these forms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lots-treatments-available-victorians-help
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There were lots of treatments available to Victorians to help them recover from psychological conditions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While there were lots treatments available, many showed serious misunderstandings about human psychology. They were ineffecive, some were inhumane and many left patients with long-term psychological damage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-words-high-modality-need
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That you should always use words with high modality (must, need, have to) to make your writing seem persuasive."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Exclusively using words with high modality can make your tone seem too direct and, therefore, make the reader feel defensive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-scientific-developments-industrial-revolution-positive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All scientific developments during the Industrial Revolution were positive in terms of their impact on society."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While the Industrial Revolution was considered to be the 'golden age' of scientific development and innovation, much of the pioneering research was conducted under unethical conditions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706974Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plot-twists-turn-happy-story
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That plot twists always turn a happy story to an unhappy story."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some classic plot twists do turn a happy story to an unhappy story, it's not true of all plot twists."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707027Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-animal-farm-unintelligent-therefore
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The animals in 'Animal Farm' are unintelligent and therefore cannot grasp complex language."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Conversely, we might suggest that the pigs' simplification of the animals' language suppresses their ability to use language to express themselves."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707237Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-language-cannot-change-facts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Language cannot change facts."@en ;
  curric:correction """The language that we use to present facts can alter people's perception of the facts and therefore, in essence, change the facts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707473Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-familiar-function-sleep-less
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may be familiar with the function of sleep, but less aware of the symbolism and connotations."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst sleep is vital for healing and serves a restorative function, it also symbolises innocence and vulnerability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-think-letter-writing-place
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some people might think that letter writing has no place in modern society."@en ;
  curric:correction """While other forms of communication have overtaken letter writing in popularity, letter writing is still necessary for many professional purposes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708022Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-individuality-associated-unique-making-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Individuality has always been associated with being unique and making your own decisions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In the sixteenth century, individuals were seen as existing as part of a network of social and family structures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708077Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-recognise-destructive-force-ambition
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may only recognise the destructive force of ambition in the play."@en ;
  curric:correction """It is also possible to consider the destructive force of guilt as central to the play."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708506Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-workhouses-positive-form-social-reform
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Workhouses were a positive form of social reform; instead of being sent to prison, poor people were offered the chance to work off any debts they had."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Workhouses were an alternative to debtor's prison but they were not positive places; inmates were separated from their families, lived in squalid conditions and forced to do hard labour for 10-12 hours a day."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708511Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-need-write-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils sometimes think they need to write out their whole presention before they deliver it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It can be much more effective to verbally plan and practice presentations without writing it in full. Approaching the tasks verbally can increase pupil confidence in articulating ideas out loud."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708516Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-individuality-celebrated-literature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Individuality is always celebrated in literature."@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, Shakespeare could be seen as demonstrating the consequences of individuality through 'Romeo and Juliet'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708520Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-parents-taken-their-childrens-wishes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That parents have always taken their children's wishes into account."@en ;
  curric:correction """In Elizabethan England, children were expected to act in a way that would benefit their family through work or marriage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708526Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-direct-almost-aggressive-your-persuasive
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That you should be very direct, almost aggressive in your persuasive writing."@en ;
  curric:correction """While directness can convey confidence, an overly direct tone can be off-putting for the recipient and cause them to become defensive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-industrial-revolution-brought-great-prosperity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Industrial Revolution brought great prosperity to the Britain; factories helped to provide wealth equality because it provided jobs to help poor people out of poverty."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Industrial Revolution did bring great prosperity but unfortunately the wealth was not shared across all social classes. Industrial wealth improved the lives of business owners but poor people suffered due to low wages and overcrowding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708704Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-perceived-hallucinations-play-summoned
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may have only perceived the hallucinations in the play as summoned by the witches."""@en ;
  curric:correction """We can read the same elements of the play through many different lenses. All interpretations are valid."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708855Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-concluding-sentences-repetition
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that concluding sentences are a repetition of topic sentences."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Concluding sentences focus on the writer's intentions and link to but do not repeat topic sentences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-naturalism-expressionism-different-cannot-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Naturalism and expressionism are too different and cannot be used together in the same play."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Arguably, Priestley blends both styles. Naturalism makes the setting realistic, while expressionism distorts reality to highlight emotional and symbolic themes, strengthening his political message."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708868Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
